A knife fight between MP3 players and cell phones.
We'll tell you how to choose
While almost every cell phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
It seems obvious that it's better to just buy a phone.
Still, there are plenty of reasons to get a standalone player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the demands of the future owner.
You're probably not going to be able to get a high-end, expensive record player at home to play the latest Maxim Turbulence album.
First, such musical products do not appear on LP records and there is no objective reason for this from a qualitative point of view.
But if you have art rock, jazz, or blues vinyl on your shelves, you probably have never dreamed of such a record.
It's the same with music on the road, so compressed music, simply, MP3 music.
There are price and quality categories here too.
It may be unacceptable for someone to spend eight thousand crowns on a record player, just as it may be difficult for a Pink Floyd fan to chew on a twenty-crown headset from the market.
Two extremes, between which there's plenty of room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It also determines the battery life
Some of the best music players can do a lot more than just play music, but most cell phones can't.
No modern device is as universal as the telephone.
In addition to the primary functions of calling and texting, it can play music and video, record both, have a better camera, a worse one, and maybe even navigate.
And if you consider smartphones and communicators, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
It's a small miracle, because no refrigerator can barbecue and no TV can photograph anything.
The universality of the mobile phone has its disadvantages.
The more features you use on your phone, the sooner the indicator on the display will send you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy drains.
Few phones can play music for more than 10 or 12 hours, but most of them can play much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
So with cheap phones, expect them to play for no more than a few hours.
If you're still making calls, get another charger at work just in case - even for more expensive devices.
You won't have that problem with MP3 players, even the worst ones will last at least nine hours of continuous playback on a single charge.
Another problem is when you record music to your phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, and not all of them can be connected directly to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly to a memory card, but few card readers can handle the miniature memory cards used in mobile phones without reducing the amount.
You don't need any special software for the iPod.
Just fill it with music via a USB drive from your computer.
Most mobile phones and players already have their own music library sorted by artist name, album name, genre, or even user rating.
Some devices only display a directory tree structure similar to Windows Explorer, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with an operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones are better
When choosing a particular device, consider in particular the battery life, the memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the comfort of operation.
If music is your main hobby and you listen to it for a short time every day, for example on the tram, you can just use any MP3 player on your phone.
Which is actually what almost any phone can do.
You don't even have to look too closely at what music formats your phone or your music player can do.
MP3s can handle everything, and the vast majority of the music that you get is going to be in that format.
It is one of the most widely used and, in addition, the vast majority of devices can also handle music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better mobile phones also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
All you have to do is visit the relevant website of the operator (or other provider) via the mobile internet and buy the song or album.
This service alone could be a strong argument for the purchase of a music mobile phone.
Unfortunately, the network's offerings are meager and mostly limited to fast-paced radio hits.
The prices aren't the lowest either.
However, it is generally expected that this method of selling music (whether via GSM, the Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their cell phones with them all the time.
Whenever you get the urge to listen to something, you grab your phone in your pocket while your MP3 player lies forgotten at home.
It also depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least a wired handsfree.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker that almost every mobile phone has, but only a minimum of MP3 players.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of music phones is that they're going to cost a lot.
The cheapest ones are usually under three grand.
For three or four thousand crowns you can already get a very decent walkman.
But most of the time, you're going to be limited by the absence of an outlet for your regular headphones.
The best and most technically-equipped phones, even with a 3.5mm headphone jack, cost up to 15,000.
The advantage of players is that they are easy to use.
The simplest - not necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - players can be mastered by anyone.
The minimal functionality, the similarity of the control to a previously common cassette player or perhaps a phonograph is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of accidentally switched on mobile internet and subsequent huge data transfer bill.
What device to touch
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (M2, microSD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of the corresponding card, you will fit into two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
For basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are supported.
Only the most expensive ones can handle 8 GB of memory.
If you already have a mobile phone and you want to buy another cheap MP3 player, go to CowOne, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgetton, or Iriver.
According to the capacity (max. 2 GB), you don't have to spend more than 1 100 CZK.
If you are a more demanding listener, you might want to reach for specialized mobile walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3s, and thus the user's comfort is close to that of a separate MP3 player.
The next largest is Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman phones have the same user interface as the MP3 players sold separately.
The same service and in the same price category up to CZK 4,000, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours maximum), you will be taken away by the MP3 players from the aforementioned brands.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe I should .
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is fairly mature and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European counterparts.
Still, we're missing something here -- a virtual operator that could make the classic ones go down.
Maybe he won't be gone long.
We have written many times on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was confirmed by the CCCME, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in the USA than in the rest of the Union.
After the European Commission's recent steps in the field of roaming charges regulation, a paradoxical situation may arise: for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there's no competition that's really willing to fight.
It may sound paradoxical, but we have three cell networks and penetration is well over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to take advantage of the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The Chairman of the Board of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who has repeatedly stated in the past that there is no room for another operator in the Czech Republic, often reminds them of this.
It is probably true that a traditional operator with its own network probably has no chance (otherwise, it would probably be difficult to find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a significant price reduction, to which the traditional operators also had to respond.
And before the likes of Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile came on the market, there were voices in the UK that sounded like ours.
But it turns out that there is a place for such operators, and they can be really successful.
Besides, we don't have to go far to get examples.
In February of this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, the operator managed to gain over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the country.
Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is that they can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to operate efficiently, they need far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not entail relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In this world, virtual operators tend to be low-cost, offering cheap calls and SMS, but this is often balanced by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half the price of its competitors.
However, as Mobilking's example in Poland shows, betting on an untouched target group can be quite a good move.
This operator is specifically targeting men.
"The right guys are going to pick Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust", says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual operator.
It is hard to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could be applied here.
Vodafone's press spokesman Miroslav Čepický doubts this: 'The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings.'
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
It seems almost certain, however, that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very promising.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries in our region", said Jana Studničková, press spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
By doing so, it indirectly confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not in favour of this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything possible to avoid any potential competition.
GTS Novera has been hiding its interest in launching a virtual mobile operator for some time, and would like to take the next step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in offering our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress with some of them", says Pavel Kaidl, the group's press spokesman.
Maybe it's a sign of things to come.
From unofficial information, it seems that we should see the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for now, its emergence is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
'At the moment we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for the emergence of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, we have not been contacted by any entity with a complex and serious project in this area", said Vlastimil Sršeň of the press department of Telefonica O2 in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with O2: 'We have not yet recorded any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to build further.'
He adds: "T-Mobile's network is unlikely to have a virtual operator by the end of the year.
At this point we should have a concrete agreement on the table to be able to think in this short term".
Vodafone is focusing more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
That's what we consider most beneficial from a customer perspective.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for high-speed mobile internet.'
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The behaviour of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
Why facilitate the entry of such a competitor?
The fact that operators can pull together when something is at stake is also shown by the pulling around the invention of the U:phone.
Perhaps the biggest push for the CTU came at the time of the invention of the U:phone by T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by the publicly available information on the CTBT website.
Now, U:fon is a good argument for not allowing a virtual operator.
Martina Kemr pointed out: 'The competitive environment in the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on it and, above all, on its services.'
However, given this approach of mobile operators, the complete lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities is quite striking.
This is not just the CMO's position, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other developed countries - does not have the power to interfere with competition.
They belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (OPCW).
But he took his typical stance on the whole issue.
'The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after a contract had been concluded between the mobile operator and the virtual operator for the lease of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential bidders was probably not sufficiently attractive for traditional operators,' said Kristián Chalupa from the external relations department of the OHIM in response to our inquiry.
I don't think that's surprising from the operators' representatives.
This is more than a compliment from an authority which is supposed to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position on the market.
In particular, as Kristián Chalupa adds: 'In foreign countries where virtual operators are common, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the reduction of mobile phone prices.'
However, it is clear that the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices are not in the interests of the EIA.
What's really shocking about this whole case is the touching agreement between the three mobile operators that emerges from their responses.
The question of whether it's really just a coincidence is a self-imposed one.
Like the exact same price of gasoline at gas stations, it is surely a product of chance and fierce competition.
'The Authority has not found any evidence of anti-competitive behaviour in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore no corresponding increased responsibility for its actions on the market.
The telecoms regulator is also likely to lack the necessary tools to open up the mobile market to virtual operators,' said Chalupa.
The interpretation of a dominant position on the market is one of the many points of contention.
Understandably, there is an analysis of the relevant markets by the OCTs which considers that telecommunications is the only market from a competitive point of view.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the consent of the network operator is always required to establish a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator -- it's quite logical -- has a monopoly on its network.
So it has to be dominant in a certain segment.
However, even if we did not accept this argument, it should be at least a warning to the ETS that the three mobile operators are behaving in a strikingly similar way.
However, the complaints of several interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all operators.
In telecommunications, blaming the CTU is a fairly common trick by which the ETS takes matters into its own hands.
We've met him on several similar occasions.
Unfortunately, until the recent amendment of the Telecommunications Act, the extension of the CTO's powers to the area of competition in telecommunications had not been implemented, although a number of experts had since promised to improve the situation.
The CSU agents must know better than that, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It's what happens when no one's watching
The operation of some pseudo-virtual operators, of which there are quite a few in the Czech mobile networks, goes unnoticed.
They are companies that publish their own mobile phone price lists, but they are only partially public.
This is because they are usually multi-level marketing companies.
It offers its own mobile phone services, such as Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these companies usually only get to the chosen few.
The magic is that the company acts towards the operator like a classic corporate customer who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a significant customer, it will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the commercial terms of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If the cases you mention occur, they could be breaches of contract that we would deal with and could result in termination of the cooperation with the company in question", Martina Kemrová replied to our question on this issue.
However, it is unlikely that such activity would not have been reported to the responsible people of the mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned above, thousands of customers may be involved.
None of the operators object to such a procedure.
The fact that they make significant profits from their activities does not jeopardise their official marketing, unlike real virtual operators.
Miroslav Čepický points out the potential problems: "The law allows for such speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name and therefore cannot have it at their disposal as regular mobile operator customers.'
But that's what should be the least weird.
In addition, a further question for the EEAS is raised.
If mobile operators are turning a blind eye to this kind of thing, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that OHIM has a rather strong power to detect such activities and, if it does not wish to, it cannot be satisfied with the operators' explanations that they were unaware of such activities and that their business conditions prohibit it.
When we're not the most expensive
As has been repeatedly stated in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a marked drop in the prices of services.
In practice, in all countries where virtual operators have been established, the traditional operators have tried to prevent them from being established to a greater or lesser extent.
The arguments used were virtually identical - too small, too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
But in developed countries, it was at this time that regulators stepped in, protecting not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they succeeded in creating the first virtual operator and enabling others to follow suit.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing this whole case away like a hot potato.
In our experience, we cannot help feeling that the ambiguity of competence is more than useful in these cases.
But let's not throw a coin at the pot.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator really does appear soon, the Czech mobile market may move again.
If one of the operators has allowed the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it is difficult for the OHIM to remain indifferent to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And we might stop calling it a raft than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Pick the best one
Listen to four performances of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the Czech State Day, solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Where is my home.
The anthem was newly recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions - with male or female solo singing, in choral performance and instrumental version.
The singing was performed by Katerina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the hymn are Otakar Jeremiah and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to all four versions on iHNed.cz.
Bělohlavek considers the Czech national anthem to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
He had previously told Czech Radio that he had deliberately chosen a singer with young representative voices, who are distinctive and popular, to sing solo versions.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure that both of them, and then the congregation, had a clear diction, that the text was well understood, that they were in agreement", he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where is my home was first performed in 1834 on the stage of the Stavovsky Theatre in the original Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyla, with music by František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously adopted it.
The first verse of the song became a natural part of the national anthem after the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
It remained one of the seven state symbols even after the establishment of the independent Czech Republic.
