Prague MHD on Wednesday for the first time even on a chip
Wednesday 1 October 2008 will go down in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passengers will board the metro, trams and buses, who will have an electronic ticket in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
It can now be purchased by about 100,000 people who own an Opencard chip.
Passengers can buy a 30-day and 90-day and a yearly coupon (it will be valid from 1 January 2009) and have it uploaded to their chip card at the information centres and workplaces of the Transport Enterprise at the underground stations Museum, Mostek, Holešovice Station, Angel, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Coupons can also be purchased online from yesterday on the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
By the afternoon, over 400 customers had used the service.
Those who start using the Internet can forget forever about the ticket counters in subway stations, where they have regularly had to stand in long lines for paper tickets.
They buy the voucher online and upload it to their Opencard at one of the 13 branches of the City Library.
"These places offer passengers a barrier with trained staff who help them with online shopping and also upload the purchased coupon to their card", said Martin Opatrný, a spokesman for the project.
In addition to libraries, it will be possible to download electronic Opencard coupons from self-service ATMs in several metro halls.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, resembling ticket markers, and passengers may have noticed them at the metro stations of Rozty, Budějovská, I. P. Pavlov, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are five in the city now, but by the end of the year there should be 80", added Opatrný.
The coupon checks the driver's seat
Operating the vending machines, which start tomorrow, is simple.
Simply insert an Opencard chip card into the card and the prepaid coupon will automatically upload to it.
Electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in the surrounding area.
This is the case for the suburban trains and bus lines numbered 300 to 499, which mainly serve the inhabitants of the Central Bohemian municipalities.
"In the trains that are part of Prague's integrated transport system, the guides are equipped with card readers that allow them to check the validity of the coupons for both time and bandwidth", explained ticket control Filip Drapal of Ropid, an organisation that compiles Prague's public transport timetables.
Suburban buses have card readers built into the driver's cash register.
The driver must not only show the chip card at the check-in, but also attach the Opencard to the designated spot on the side of the ticket office.
This will allow the driver to check the validity of the downloaded coupons.
"If a passenger needs to verify the validity of a downloaded coupon, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information", added the Grappler.
Passengers who do not travel by bus and do not remember when their voucher expires can go back to the ATM where vouchers are loaded onto the card.
Here, information on the validity of their documents is displayed on the instrument display.
The Sudetenland wanted a referendum on the United States.
The Sudeten Germans in 1945 requested the incorporation of the Shumava into the United States.
It's from a letter that's in the South Bohemian Science Library.
If we can't be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live under the auspices of the United States of America.
In 1945, a group of Sudeten Germans reportedly appealed to the president of the United States with this request.
This is evident, among other things, from a letter that was kept in a private archive and is now stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Český Krumlov are asking the American president in a letter not to allow the return of the "Sumav County" - taken by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - back to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and want to be really sure in words that American troops are coming to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators", reads the letter, signed "People who care about the fate of the Schumacher".
Since annexation to Czechoslovakia supposedly gives the Sudeten Germans - with knowledge of the Czech national character - hope only for brutality, ruthlessness, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter beg the American president to take over the Šumava protectorate for the present and eternal times.
"We cannot believe that you, despite the opinion of a quarter of a million people, would give this territory to some foreign state that oppresses and rejects minorities and has done nothing but contribute to the Allied victory", the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is fear of the vengeance of the "Czech oppressors".
If the President of the United States was supposed to doubt the thinking of the Schumacher Germans, all he had to do was to hold a referendum in Schumacher County on whether its citizens wanted to become part of the United States or live under the auspices of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound a bit naive in today's knowledge of postwar history, some scholars say it aptly reflects the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at the time.
