Even rats have feelings
When a rat or a cockroach runs away from danger, does that mean they also feel fear?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux believes that many animals have feelings, too.
But how would we know if they feel the same way when they behave like us?
For several years now, the online magazine "Edge" has been publishing contributions from prominent scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents selected answers to the question "What do you believe to be true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness that I or anyone else has been able to prove, if we can't prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
But once we start to look at another species and open up the question of perception or consciousness in general, we're entering a difficult terrain because the hardware doesn't fit.
When a rat is in danger, it will do what many other animals do: pretend to be dead, run away, or attack.
People behave similarly, which some scientists conclude is a comparable subjective experience.
I don't believe that, though.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to translate our subjective experience into animal experience.
This is because circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and executive or control functions).
This vast area is significantly more developed in humans than in other primates, and it seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including knowing who we are and the ability to plan and make decisions, there is reason to believe that humans are different even from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie hidden in the linguistic nature of man: because so much of his perception is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, we could exclude animals.
But even if language did not matter, it would certainly be affected by language, so animal consciousness, whatever its construction, would probably differ from most states of consciousness in humans.
That's why it's difficult to know what consciousness might look like in other animals.
When something is intrinsic and subjective, and it cannot be measured or analyzed, because of the special hardware, based on our own experience, it puts us in a great problem to explore it.
Most of my conclusions relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more accessible scientifically.
It would be possible to study the processes in the mind of animals regardless of their content, and that's exactly what happens in studies of short-term memory in primates, especially in the case of visualization.
But this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick have been working on, focuses more on neural correlates of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: they may be identical, but they may not be.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the neofrontal cortex for visualization.
What does that mean for feelings?
I derive them from the fact that an emotional system, like the fear system, is activated in the brain by conscious activity.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state we're in when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as bodily reactions) uses operational memory.
So, from this angle, feelings are closely linked to those areas of the cortex that are characteristic of primates, and especially humans.
In connection with the nature of language, there is a subtle gradation of perception, because with words and grammar we can distinguish and categorize states so that we can attribute them to others besides ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations arise from more primitive activities in areas of the cortex and brain stem that are devoted to bodily sensations, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much over the course of human evolution, it could easily share the senses perceived by multiple animal species.
I can't argue with that, but I find it unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what we see as fear in rats and humans is likely to be felt by both organisms in the same way: But how can we verify, Pankseep continues, that rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
The cockroach fleeing danger - does it also feel fear?
In my view, the mere similarity of behavior cannot prove the similarity of experience.
It's true that neural comparisons take us further: rats and humans have similar brain stem, whereas cockroaches have no brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for the feelings?
And even if we could prove it in humans, how would we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have feelings.
But I don't really know how to prove it.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I'd rather study emotional behavior than rat emotional perception.
Anyway, we can see progress at the neural level in this case if we measure the same in rats and humans.
I don't study language and consciousness, nor do I study feelings, because I don't know if they exist.
It may seem short-sighted, but I'd rather move forward than slam myself against a wall repeatedly.
I'm a practical emotional writer.
