The Obama campaign points out that "African-American and Hispanic students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students", which is true.
To combat such performance gaps, Obama's education agenda specifically promotes, among other things, "transitional bilingual education" for those just learning English.
The question remains, however, whether Barack Obama's commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes using languages other than English in the classroom, is stronger than his interest in reducing performance gaps.
Take Sixth Street Prep, for example, a charter elementary school in East Los Angeles County.
The students at this school are, in the vast majority of cases, Hispanics from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have only recently arrived, are learning English.
Yet, in the 2008 state math tests, an incredible 100 percent of fourth graders scored at the top.
