This incredible achievement was achieved by a different method than Obama's preferred.
Sixth Street emphasizes control and practice, constant assessment of ability and an approach without excuses.
And then, and Obama should note, according to Linda Mikels, the director of Sixth Street, the school's approach to teaching English for those just learning is "full immersion".
The immersion in English emphasizes the almost privileged use of English in teaching.
Miss Mikels, who is against bilingual education, told me, "We've had tremendous success with one new student from Mexico -- after 12 months, you'd walk into a classroom and you wouldn't know who he was".
"It works", she declared, "it works for us".
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model of what other schools with large Hispanic and English-language student populations should look like?
The results the school is achieving should make the answer to this question self-evident, but his own party's educational agenda (the National Education Association is a long-time advocate of bilingual education) and his own consistent support for bilingual education cloud the predictions of Obama's answer.
