"I've never seen anything like it", said Ellis.
The second quarter began after the Jets and Arizona Cardinals played their agonizing game against the grim clouds above.
Then quarterback Brett Favre sent Laveranuese Coles on a 12-yard touchdown run, perfectly foreshadowing an afternoon in which their gradually developing collaboration moved a mile forward.
Favre sent Coles in for two more touchdowns in that quarter, including one that landed the cornerback, and another 10 seconds before halftime.
"It was nothing extraordinary", Favre said of all his passing to Coles.
"He's a hell of a player.
We communicated well, no matter what people thought".
While Favre and Coles were throwing, the defense attacked Cardinals quarterback Kurt Warner.
Cornerback Darelle Revis caught a pass and returned it 32 yards for a touchdown.
Safety Eric Smith has a second pass and he's got it.
Linebacker David Bowens has Warner on the fence.
The last ball drop, the fumble that Bowens forced, was perhaps the best ever.
The Cardinals got to the ball 10 seconds before the end, and after the Jets got the ball back, Jay Feely kicked a 20-yard field goal to take a 34-0 lead.
That's the most the Jets have ever scored in a quarter.
Jets coach Eric Mangini, when asked to describe the insanity, said, "Second quarter or third quarter?"
When told that both - the Jets allowed 21 unanswered points in the third quarter - Mangini said: "I can tell you that I enjoyed the second quarter much more than the third.
A lot of points have fallen in a short period of time".
The first Gebreselassie to improve his world record
Haile Gebreselassie of Ethiopia once again showed why he is considered by many to be the greatest long-distance runner of all time when he broke his own world record at the Berlin Marathon on Sunday, becoming the first person to run the 26.2-mile race in under two hours and four minutes.
Winning the flat track in 2:03:59 he beat his previous time of 2:04:26 which he ran last year in Berlin by 27 seconds.
Gebreselassie, 35, has set the 26th world record of his career, which is really incredibly wide - he has broken the world record or at least is the world champion at all distances from the metric mile to the marathon.
Last month Gebreselassie skipped the Beijing Olympic marathon because he feared - perhaps too frightened in hindsight - that air pollution would irritate his asthma problems.
Instead, he promised to run in Berlin.
In near-perfect conditions - sunny and 48 degrees at the start, 55 degrees at the finish - he won the Gebreselassie on Sunday with a lightning-fast average of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
What track runners like Gebreselassie and Paul Tergat of Kenya have focused on is the longer track, the marathon record for the past decade having fallen by more than two minutes since Brazil's Ronaldo da Costa won in Berlin in 2:06:05 in 1998.
After Sunday's victory, Gebreselassie told reporters that he had had calf cramps two weeks ago and missed a week of training.
The break obviously got him up rather than down.
"I'm so happy", Gebreselassie told reporters, "I'm not going to be able to do it".
"Everything was perfect.
I started again a week ago, and I was a little hesitant today, but everything was fine".
He has also been criticized - especially in Kenya, the East African rival of Ethiopia - for allegedly over-planning his races, generally avoiding world marathon peaks, relying on drivers as if it were a track race, and putting world records above the point of competition.
But this criticism can hardly diminish Gebreselassie's tremendous running qualities.
Maintained at the pace by four Kenyans, Gebreselassie reached the half in a time of 1:02:04.
After the drivers dropped, Gebreselassie was constantly being chased by two elite Kenyan runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi.
Just before three miles from the finish line in Gebreselassie, he took the last and ran out to Kwambai, who then finished second in 2:05:36, improving his personal best by almost five minutes.
Kamathi finished third in 2:07:48.
In the women's race, Irina Mikitenko, a native of Kazakhstan who is now a German citizen, finished the year with the seventh fastest time in history at 2:19:19.
The record time of 2:15:25 is held by Paula Radcliff from Great Britain.
Thirty-six-year-old Mikitenko surprisingly won the London Marathon last spring in a time of 2:24:14.
She missed the Beijing Games because of what was described as a back injury, but recovered and won in Berlin, and in the third marathon she's ever run, she improved her personal best by almost five minutes.
She ran the race cleverly and thoughtfully, letting four Ethiopian and Kenyan runners run a good lead and then overtaking them at about 18 1⁄2 miles.
Askalefa Magarsa of Ethiopia finished second in 2:21:31 and Helene Kiprop of Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
The Pride and Obstacles of Separate City Black Life
Hidden among the sprawling amusement parks of Greater Orlando, a few miles from all that glitters, noises and swells, lies a quiet city that brings to life the pride and the hardships of African-American life.
Eatonville, the first all-black city to be incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "a city of five lakes, three croquet courts, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, plenty of hay, two schools, and no prisons".
It's a pilgrimage site now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Eatonville Dawn! Festival to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains a side note, even though it has become a tourist destination by including it in the Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers Project during the Depression.
It is still as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their true feelings with the white man, who "knows so little about us that he does not know what he is missing".
Even today, in a year when black presidential candidate Senator Barack Obama is calling for an open debate on race, many here remain wary of the views of outsiders.
"We are very careful about how our story is told", says 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the city's oldest parish.
"It has to be right".
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It's both a historical model of black upward mobility, and a community of nearly 2,400 people, where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It's a center of literature, but it's also a shadowy example of the Southern rural black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes praised - that emerged from American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the people here are both proud and protective.
And the concern about the Eatonville idea really didn't start until Zora, which is the only way Hurstons are called here.
She introduced her hometown to the world through heartfelt, tongue-in-cheek books such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
The five paragraph Florida tourist guide has turned the city into a little bit of Route 17, which leads through the often-overlooked center of Florida, into a stage for black history and human drama.
With a big bang in life and literature, Hurston introduced readers to the business of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"On the left side of the road", she wrote, "is a white-brown, modern national school with well-maintained courtyards and playground, always tended by Howard Miller, though he cannot read or write very well".
She also mentioned Dash's widow's new husband, and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and anything else that fits in the hotel's watch".
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, remarriage and sex.
This was obviously not your typical Fodor's publishing house.
It wasn't really a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
"She told it like it was", says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, a member of the Johnson Girls, who Hurston made immortal by quoting men who sang silly songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it", she added.
Hurston is still remembered here as a cyborg freak who often returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalls that most of the time when she arrived in town, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still prides itself on its modesty.
Most of the population was fascinated, Franklin said, but many were disgusted.
"People have always liked to see the dawn", said Franklin.
But, he added, swinging from a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "never stayed too long".
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
It seemed Eatonville, along with the rest of the world, had forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had lived before.
There was no major mourning ceremony or major public reading in Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood her importance to the world or her legacy at all", said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's 2003 biography, Wrapped in Rainbows.
The change came in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to extend the city's five-lane highway instead of Kennedy Boulevard, the local two-lane highway.
The Orlando split has already pushed Interstate 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult historical period.
The forced integration, among other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred to the threshold of the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white boys, they came and threw oranges and stuff at people who were sitting on the side", Franklin said.
"Actually, we had a lady here who was killed by it.
They threw a melon out of the car".
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston challenged the Supreme Court's demand for forced integration and declared its decision in Brown v. Board of Education "offensive rather than celebratory to my race".
Residents now argue that the desegregation of schools, while positive in some areas, has reduced Eatonville's cohesion and undermined the morale of the local youth.
"Black children were used to hugging - I remember it - you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening", said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Elly Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
This lasted until the teachers and students came from the same place, she added.
"You don't hug your white teacher because your white teacher - I mean, there's a cultural barrier", said Ms. Nathiri.
Civil rights, however, helped create space for many more Dawn Neale Hurston - black writers, actors and artists who, like her, rose above prejudice with light-hearted self-esteem and quotes like "How can anyone deny the pleasure of my presence!
I don't understand that".
In 1975, Alice Walker made her way to Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight to revive her reputation.
Five years later, a highly praised biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway appeared on bookshelves, re-entering the American canon.
The highway project arrived just as Eatonville's most famous daughter was once again finding the light of day.
The Hurstons' former neighbors now considered her a savior.
To show what could happen to their highway, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived for the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return to celebrate.
The state backed down from the highway project after a few years.
"The five streams of the highway have revived, you would say, a real sense of civic pride", said Nathiri.
Boyd said it more simply, "The dawn saved Eatonville".
The victory over the highway project helped change the image of the city.
Outsiders like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began attending the local church in 1993, began to appear in greater numbers, and residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and redecorated Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes seem like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Today, it is 90 percent black.)
Strangers who come to seek the history and significance of Eatonville are still often treated with caution.
Permission is required for most interviews, and certain things - such as murals in Eatonville's oldest church, painted by white people and depicting blacks in fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Jones, the brave, confident teacher who likes to eat red, are still afraid that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
And as the Hurston Festival grew, so did the pride of home.
Young people in particular tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, troubled and so on, but not better, not worse, and as proud, creative, hardworking, silly and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
The voice of Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, sounds like a sincere love for the village as he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work for local government or the police, which he says would use some help.
And even younger ones, like the 11-year-old twins Alondra and Alexia Kenon from Winter Park, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, when they pass by, think, 'Hmm, this town is nothing against the others,'" said Alondra Kenon recently after church on Sunday.
"But if you really stop and look for a moment into history, it's a very nice city".
Here in New York we all speak fluent financials
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newsstands and the giant TV screens in Times Square, they wouldn't realize they were standing in the middle of a storm.
They would never guess that in the stained-glass beehive of offices above their heads, every day the bankers and hedge fund managers who monopolize New York City have the worst "bad day at the office" since the crash of 1929.
The messengers are still hauling metal trolleys down the sidewalks and carrying muffin bakers to breakfast meetings.
The Spaniards keep moving between the towers, wearing, like human mules, fifty-fifty iron shirts hanging from the pendants on their backs.
Office rats are still lining up at street food stalls for their morning bagels, and it's still impossible to get a yellow cab on a weekday between 4 and 7 p.m.
It didn't seem like a crisis at all until, with all the talk of pessimism, I decided to open a savings account on a Thursday afternoon.
Even though I timed this task to cover a late afternoon nap at my local J.P. Morgan Chase office, there were already about 20 people waiting in line.
Not in front of the cash registers to pick up or deposit cash, but in front of the counter where senior customers order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to Macy's, and new customers open accounts.
Most of the people before me, as I learned from Starr, my "licensed personal banker", came for the same reason I did.
But by my time, they had already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks in places like New Jersey, Pennsylvania, or Staten Island.
They have taken money from so-called thrift shops (similar to building societies), money associations and those types of savings banks that operate in only one state and claim to care for their customers like a family.
In the past year, 15 such banks have quietly failed.
A few days ago, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went bankrupt, and as New Yorkers returned home for the weekend on Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion in assets, was trying to find a buyer to bail it out.
The office and store workers who stood in front of me and feared another collapse were moving their cash to a bank that is seen as a safe haven and that does most of the bailouts on Wall Street.
Ordinary New Yorkers have learned financial fluency in the last week.
A woman at my local Chinese supermarket was on the phone, talking to Lehman Borthers, the failed bank, and its thin CEO, Dick Fuld, with a familiarity that was like she was taunting a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed, 50-something housekeeper in my apartment, changed the subject of our usual conversation - Brad, Angelina, or my food delivery.
After my visit to the bank, she said: "I have my savings in money market funds now.
I've moved it, I'm not taking any chances".
Muslim graves desecrated after Austrian right-wing crackdown
Heinz-Christian Strache, left, from the Austrian right-wing Free Party, and Filip Dewinter from the Belgian right-wing Vlaams Belang, take part in a demonstration presented by the organization "Cities Against Islamization" in Antwerp on Thursday, 17 January 2008.
They carry signs similar to traffic signs, which show mosques crossed by a red line.
Police accuse right-wing extremists of desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria on the same weekend that far-right parties made huge gains in the general election.
Over 90 graves in the cemetery in the town of Traun near Linz were severely damaged between Friday night and this morning and police believe it was an organized act.
The perpetrators sprayed Jewish symbols such as the Star of David on some graves, but detectives believe it may have been an attempt to mask the motives of extremists who hate Muslim immigrants.
It's unclear if this incident was in any way connected to the election.
A spokesman for the Muslim community there said they were "deeply shocked" by reports of desecration, which came as the Muslim fasting month of Ramadan drew to a close.
Meanwhile, Austria is entering a cycle of self-searching after the right-wing shift in last week's parliamentary elections.
The two far-right parties, which collectively won more than 30 percent of the vote, the Free Party and the Union for the Future of Austria, have been vigorously campaigning against immigration, and some of their slogans have been criticized as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, the leader of the Free Party, which won over 18 percent of the vote, campaigned against the headscarves and burkas, and even expressed his opposition to foods that are perceived to be related to Islam.
At his last meeting with voters in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the rise of Islam.
Both parties are trying to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, arguing that they are political symbols of the ongoing Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses carried out immediately after the elections, which positioned the far right as the most powerful political bloc in the country, suggest that this change was caused primarily by young voters who are worried about their future in the European Union.
Gary Glitter is not allowed to go on a trip overseas.
Gary Glitter, the glam rock star convicted of child sexual abuse, has been banned from traveling to France and Spain.
Officials imposed this six-month ban on Glitter after he informed the monitoring authorities that he planned to travel via France to Spain.
Kent police were granted a travel ban last Thursday after handing over evidence of Glitter's past convictions for child sexual abuse.
Glitter, under his real name Paul Gadd, did not attend the hearing at Ashford Court of Common Pleas in Kent, but was represented by lawyers from Corker Binning.
A spokesman for the judiciary said: "On Thursday 25 September, Kent Police applied to Ashford Court of First Instance for an order to prevent Mr Paul Gadd from crossing the border into France and Spain until 25 March.
Paul Gadd was not personally involved".
64-year-old Glitter has informed authorities that he wishes to travel abroad, as he is making a record of sexual assault.
He must notify the authorities if he wants to travel abroad for more than three days.
He must also give the police the planned departure date a week in advance.
If he neglected to inform the authorities, he could be sentenced to five years.
Kent police have announced they will not be investigating individual cases of Glitter's possible travels around the county.
A spokesman for the Kent Police said: "Kent Police will do whatever is necessary to protect children in this country or abroad.
From our point of view, it's easier to track someone who stays in the UK because we have extensive systems here that handle potential dangers more effectively.
Protecting Kent residents is a top priority for Kent Police, and we are working diligently to monitor the behavior of registered sex offenders to minimize any danger to the public".
Glitter returned to Britain last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for molesting two girls aged 10 and 11.
When he was released, he flew to Bangkok to board a flight to London.
But he said he wasn't feeling well, and he refused to fly to London.
Thai authorities did not let him pass passport control and he eventually flew to Hong Kong.
He was also refused entry by Chinese authorities and he flew back to Bangkok, where Thai police and immigration officials insisted on his return to Britain.
On 22 August, he finally arrived at Heathrow Terminal 3 and remained there while his lawyer David Corker went to the Uxbridge Court of Criminal Appeal in West London, and at the same time Scotland Yard successfully sought an order that he be registered as a sex offender.
Glitter was previously jailed for four months in the UK for possession of child pornography.
A source at the Interior Department said Jacqui Smith, the Interior Secretary, is calm and happy that Glitter has been prevented from traveling to France and Spain.
"To capture the real character, I photograph the master off stage". Günther Bauer - photographer
No heels, no calls, no costumes. I'm not going to be a cop.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, detached from the focus on interpretation - only then will I achieve a relaxed expression of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
The second one is a human.
Inseparable, let alone private, in those moments away from the audience - when you can see the intimate gesture, the depth of the eye that is caught or the passionate gesture of the hands that are carefree because they are not going to come out on stage.
German Günther Bauer alternates the theatrical nature of the flamenco-people with the singers, dancers and guitarists with the lesser-known faces of the masters.
With this in mind, the photographer is compiling a unique iconography of flamenco from different environments.
The exhibition, held as part of the monthly programme of flamenco photography (Mes de la Fotografía Flamenca), "reflects the ever-growing international importance of flamenco", says the author, explaining that the "Flamenco-people" "can be any people, but when you look at the photographs, you will see that they are not the typical images of artists on stage.
These people portrayed "on the street" are artists who are able to bring passion, sadness, joy to the stage and completely captivate the audience.
You don't have to be on stage to capture the personalities of these artists.
He carries his personality and character inside.
I was interested in creating a relaxed atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of the great flamenco.
Fascinated by the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer began in 1997 a long journey of portraying flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers for the record camera.
These are portraits that, by choice of camera and material, resemble classic photography.
The application of different stylistic means contradicts the classical basis of the image and lends it a contemporary spirit, an idea that according to Bauer himself reflects flamenco: "Music with very traditional roots, but which does not cease to surprise and develop".
What draws the audience is not the effect of the dance, the singing, or the play itself, but the personality and character of the performer.
The search for the moment in which we encounter the most essential, the spirit that manifests itself in the way of perceiving, being and experiencing, has been and is a constant of the work presented during these days in the gallery El Fotomata.
This selection of almost 70 photographed artists is made up of well-known flamenco figures such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales and Vicente Amigo, among others.
The project has become a kind of anthology of flamenco and will soon be published in book form, with the portraits on display.
Two years ago, Bauer's passion for portraiture led him to the idea of repeating it in the "Portraits of Sports Veterans" ("SportARTproject").
Although their concept is different from "Flamenco-people", the photographer admits that "to photograph people, to get to know them and to be able to enter their lives for a moment, whether it is longer or just short - that is my passion.
I think in photography, portrait is the most difficult genre.
You meet or encounter people, personalities that you don't even know, or who give you just a few minutes to take a picture.
Despite similar circumstances, as a photographer I always try to make my imaginations come true".
A collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco called "Flamenco-people" is on display at the Galerie El Fotómata at 20 de la Mata, parallel to the Alameda de Hércules, and can be visited until 16 October.
Vargas Llosa has admitted that the novel he's writing is "a blunder"
Set in an environment he has yet to experience and telling of events unknown to him, Mario Vargas Llosa is determined to succeed in his new project - he is currently working on a novel starring Roger Casemant, an Irish nationalist who has lived in the Congo for twenty years and has also travelled in the Amazon.
The perennial favorite of the Nobel Prize for Literature admitted yesterday at the Hay Festival in Segovia that the project he is currently working on is "a boldness" and that "everything suggests that I should not write" this novel.
"If I had any sense, I wouldn't do it, but I will do it and I believe I will finish it one day", he concluded his speech at a festival of exchange of ideas, thoughts and words that over four days saw the city aqueduct around hundreds of writers, historians and journalists and thousands of other people.
The author of "The City and the Dogs" was one of the main characters of the third annual Word Festival and fulfilled expectations.
Vargas Llosa, winner of the Hay Festival's prize for best writer - an old edition of Dickens' "Our mutual friend" - filled the Juan Bravo Theatre to the last place.
With Félix Rome presenting it, he had before him a devoted audience, for whom the hour of time had passed like water - the Peruvian recalled with amazing precision and a noteworthy dose of humor how from the original "incredible adventure" from the "pleasure of an avid reader" and from "the power to live more than I have lived" a literary mission was born; how he compensates for "the lack of inspiration" by writing "disciplinedly", meticulously sorting, correcting and rewriting the text; or how Faulkner, Victor Hugo and Alexandre Dumas have influenced his writing and what "memorial images" are the foundation of his stories.
The Spanish-American novelist admitted that "there is no way" to know whether and to what extent books can change lives, "but I refuse to believe that literature is merely entertainment, a fleeting experience", Vargas Llosa stressed, saying that "people are affected" and "the aim is to try to break the rules", and urged writers to "not succumb to frivolity" and "take responsibility" for their mission.
