They ran a check in Álava in a van with 2,000 kilograms of hashish.
Ten minutes to five.
Road control of Ertzaintza in the municipality of Armiñón (Álava).
The authorities stop two people in a van and they get away.
A shipment of more than two tons of hashish is unstoppable.
According to the report of the Department of Interior of the Basque Government, the authorities pursued and detained one of the persons travelling in the van, a 38-year-old man who was identified as A. A. J.
The suspect was charged with drug trafficking and forgery of government documents.
The incident occurred when several members of the Transport Unit were conducting a road check on the N-1 in places where it crosses the border of the Armiñón urban district.
They were about to stop the van for a check, but the driver disobeyed instructions, accelerated violently and fled.
Officers immediately began to chase the car until it stopped at a curb a few miles away, at which point both passengers jumped out and fled into the wooded area.
Ertzaintz officials eventually caught up with one of them and seized 2,178 kilograms of hashish that the suspects were carrying, as revealed during a search of an Iveco Daily delivery.
The rear of the vehicle was loaded with packages of hashish, which were subsequently transferred to other police departments for detailed expertise and weighing of the drugs.
In addition, the police found that the license plate was "smeared" and did not match the data given in the delivery documents, so the detainee was also charged with forging state documents.
The Ertzaintza continues to search for the second suspect, who, as mentioned earlier, managed to escape, in order to finally determine the origin of the seized drugs.
Detained A. A. J., 28 years old, was taken to the police station for the completion of the necessary formalities before further investigation is commenced.
Actress Heather Locklear arrested for driving under the influence of drugs
Actress Heather Locklear, the favorite Amanda from Melrose Place, was arrested in Santa Barbara, California, this weekend for driving under the influence.
A witness saw her perform unusual maneuvers as she tried to get out of the Montecito parking lot, a spokesman for the California Highway Patrol told People magazine.
The witness said that at about 4:30 p.m., Locklear "was stepping on the gas, swerving back and forth with a loud rumbling, and trying to get out of the parking lot - she had broken her sunglasses several times while backing off".
A witness, who apparently did not recognize the actress at first, saw Locklear moments after she stopped at a nearby highway and got out of the vehicle.
This person also alerted the emergency services because "she was afraid for Locklear's life".
When the police patrol arrived at the scene, they found the actress inside a vehicle that partially blocked the road.
"She looked disoriented", so the authorities took her to a specialized drug and alcohol center to be tested.
A police spokesman said the actress cooperated and an excessive amount of alcohol was subsequently ruled out, but "we believe Locklear was under the influence of some drugs, which was apparent to the officers at first sight".
Locklear was arrested on suspicion of driving under the influence of an unspecified substance and taken into custody at around 7pm, although she was released a few hours later.
Two months ago, Locklear returned from a treatment clinic where she was recovering from anxiety and depression.
Llamazares urges the Andalusian IU Association to exercise its powers in the Silva case
The head of the IU and the MP for the United Left, Gaspar Llamazares, said today that the final decision in the case of the former council member of the Youth and Sports Department of the Seville mayor, Francisca Manuel Silva, who resigned from office last week after being accused of acting in favor of his family, will depend on the regional association of the party.
"I am too much of a federalist to do this, it is up to the Andalusian organization to exercise its powers", Llamazares suggested the negotiations the party will have to undertake in relation to the former member of the Seville city council.
However, the head of IU insisted that "transparency" is absolutely necessary in the case of investigating the illegal actions committed by Silva: "The IU has always fought for the maximum transparency in such matters".
He also stressed that the party has a "strict code of ethics for all public functions".
"Sangre de mayo", an epic gamble by Garcia
José Luis Garci's Sangre de Mayo, inspired by Episodes from the National Past by Benito Pérez Galdós, brings to life the famous revolt of the Spanish against the French - the most ambitious film in his filmography with a budget of around €15 million.
In this way, the filmmaker wanted to "draw the eloquence of the characters and the analysis of society" that he always admired in the work of the famous novelist, he explained today, together with Quim Gutiérrez and Paula Echevarría, during the presentation of the film to a large team of interpreters.
The two-and-a-half-hour film Blood of Flowers will be released in cinemas this Friday, and a four-hour TV series is planned for Telemadrid in the future.
As a great admirer of the literary work of Galdós José Luis Garci, he claims that by making this film he has fulfilled his "childhood dream", thanks to Esperanza Aguirre, who three years ago commissioned him to make a film for the Autonomous Province of Madrid to mark the bicentenary of Madrid on May 2, he accepted the offer with the idea that the plot would be based on an episode of the national past.
The 15 million budget, fully funded by the Madrid provinces, is a "unique opportunity" for Garcia to create an environment with sets and costumes that reflect the image of "a shaky Spain that has been mistaken for a leader to fight for - the struggle for independence led to the decline and backwardness of the country under the reign of Ferdinand VII", he said.
The director regrets that he cannot count on the financial support received for the films Ala triste or Goya's ghosts - almost twice as much as Bloody Flower - so he could not shoot some scenes from the script signed at the same time by Horacio Valcarcel, with whom he has worked for almost his entire film career.
The director of "Volver a empezar" (Starting Again) works as he is accustomed to - on stage with actors he usually auditions with before filming and does not cast because he finds it "humiliating" and also believes that "part of the job of a director is to go to theaters and cinemas and see what is going on in the craft he is doing".
Many of the actors he chose for Blood of Flowers have appeared before his camera in a few different ways, such as Miguel Rellán, Carlos Larrañaga or Fernando Guillén Cuervo.
Garci, who has four Oscar nominations, one of which he won, believes that none of the three candidates representing Spain at the Hollywood Academy this year, Bloody Flower, Seven Tables of French Billiards and the latest selection, Blind Sunflowers, represent the young generation of the Spanish film scene, but he claims that "it is just coming".
Garci doesn't expect any awards for this movie.
"At first you think you're working for what's next, but then you realize you're only working for profit, so you're willing to make one more movie", explains Garci, who has been directing for over 30 years.
Isabel Bayón revives the spiritual legacy of the Sevillian dancer Tortola Valencia
The Sevillian flamenco dancer pays tribute to another Sevillian dancer.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia, of Catalan father Florenç Tórtola Ferrer and Andalusian mother Georgina Valencia Valenzuela, was born in Triana, and moved to London with her family when she was three.
She danced modern dance and focused on oriental dancing.
She lived a life of passion, she was a pioneer of women's emancipation like Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist and a vegetarian, and she fought to abolish the corset, which prevented women from moving freely.
The life of this woman, influenced by the dance and aesthetic revolution of interwar Europe, was enchanting to Isabella Bayona.
"I wanted to work with Peppa Gamboa, and she designed this character for me -- it seemed incredible".
According to the dancer, "it's not about telling her life, it's about capturing her soul.
The titles of her dance performances reminded me of the rhythms of flamenco.
So "butterfly dance" evoked a guajira or "snake dance" some tango.
Her dance was sensual and I was told that my dance matched that aesthetic", she says.
The performance features two exceptional personalities: Miguel Vedda, who will sing Isabella in one performance, as in "La puerta abierta", and the dance teacher Matilde Coral, who made an exception and agreed to collaborate with her former pupil.
"Matilde is the older Tortola, a mature figure.
I am happy that she accepted the offer to work on my project, and it is a great honor".
The performance also features music and guitars by Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, singing by Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; drums by El Pájara, viola by Rafa El Viola and the collaboration of actress Juanfra Juárez, "who has the role of eternal guide of this kind of artists, who are primadas with everything and who are always in love with them".
The work also takes into account the life of this woman, which took place in her time in places as far away as India, the United States, or Russia, and also throughout Europe, as she usually lived in London.
"I wanted to remember her because I think she was one of those women who had a huge influence at one time, but no one knows her today, and even less appreciates her work", says Bayón.
The show starts today at 8:30 at the Lope de Vegy Theatre.
The book "Diary of a Newlywed" also closes the triennial
The presentation of the first illustrated edition of the "Diary of a Newlywed Man" in Saint Stephen's Church (New York), at the site where Juan Ramón Jiménez married Zenobia in March 1916, is part of a programme coordinated by the Cultural Council of the Autonomous Government of Andalusia to celebrate the "Triennale of Zenobia and Juan Ramón" (2006-2008), organized to celebrate the fiftieth anniversary of the award of the Nobel Prize for Literature and the anniversary of their deaths.
The "Triennale of Zenobia and Juan Ramón" is coming to an end with the new edition of this work, an international congress to be held in New York, the renovation of the Nobel House Museum and the traveling exhibition "Juan Ramón Jiménez: One Sunbeam", which opened in May of this year and, after touring various provinces of Andalusia, is scheduled to move to New York at the time of the congress.
The Cultural Council of the Autonomous Government of Andalusia also ordered eight hundred copies of "Diary of a Newlywed Man" edited by Pedro Taberner and illustrated by Jacob Pérez-Encis, to continue spreading awareness about the personality and work of one of the most world-famous Andalusian poets.
