Drivers repeatedly caught with alcohol in their blood will have to install an "alcolock"
The Ministry of the Interior requires that a driver with three administrative penalties for driving under the influence of alcohol must install a system in his car that prevents him from starting the car when drunk or if he is not breathing.
The proposal was made public in June this year and is now included in the annual report of the High Prosecutor's Office, which says it is a pilot project for one year.
The aim is to get the driver back behind the wheel, so drivers will also have to take a road re-education course.
In addition to the National Road Safety Authority, the Directorate-General for Transport (DGT) and the Foundation of the Technological Institute for Automotive Safety (FITSA) will also participate in this experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75 percent of motorists charged with more than one drunk driving offense will re-sit behind the wheel.
Alcolock should prevent this, as it is a system attached to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not breathe first or if higher than the permitted alcohol concentration is recorded.
The price is over 1000 euros and the perpetrator himself would have to pay it.
A study in this respect carried out in the USA in 2007 showed that the number of offenses on vehicles fitted with this device decreased by 65% during the first year of implementation.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address this behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And to facilitate its implementation, since legislation can be implemented in the usual way, the necessary reform of the criminal provisions requires an amendment of the law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial version, although it has already been installed in some industrial and public service vehicles in a test run.
Tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on the proposal of the PSOE (Spanish Socialist Workers' Party) which recommends that the system be installed in school buses, as is the case in France.
