Talking in your sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I don't mean the ones who wake up and tell us something that happened the day before, but the children who talk while they sleep.
When it happens for the first time, it may scare you, but it's really insignificant.
It's a harmless sleep disorder called somnolence.
It's pretty common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure some of you have heard that he spoke in his sleep at night.
This may occur very sporadically (e.g. once in a lifetime in cases of high fever) or more regularly (every day, once a week, once every few months...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There's no single reason for her coming.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night rabies, nocturnal enuresis (night sweats), or menstruation, but this is not necessarily the case.
As mentioned earlier, it can often be accompanied by very high fevers, stress, or wakefulness.
In any case, it is a little-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears also varies.
The child may speak in a calm voice, say individual words, whisper, or vice versa (screams, crying, long speeches, etc.).
In cases where it manifests with great force, it would be appropriate to observe the child and consult a specialist to see if there is any problem that causes great anxiety and manifests itself in this way.
We said it was a harmless disorder, so it's not curable unless it's associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (like if it's associated with apnea syndrome or chronic stress).
But we can do this by keeping in mind a few very simple precautions, such as:
Try not to upset the baby too much before he goes to bed.
So seek out calm games and avoid frightening or somewhat violent TV programs or series.
For very nervous children and those who are difficult to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain a measure of inner calm.
This will allow the baby to sleep more peacefully.
If somnolence appears, try to remain calm.
Remember that it is harmless to the child and that he will not remember anything the next day.
Helpful Tips
Don't be the one.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'll interrupt his sleep.
Even when he talks, he sleeps, and therefore he rests.
Remember, if you have repeatedly felt that your child is very distressed, it may be appropriate to seek counsel or to find out what is causing the distress.
If you can understand what he is saying (which is not so common), avoid the temptation to question him and to extract information.
It won't do any good, because when he's asleep, he's not conscious enough to organize his thoughts.
Furthermore, you may hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming about or why he is saying it, so be very careful how you interpret the information and draw your own conclusions.
Never tell a child that you can ask him about his secret at night.
Not for fun.
It's very distressing.
Just don't worry, it's not a bad thing, it's just an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
