Interview - Blood That is Sure Again
Yesterday, Héma-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightly delighted that Héma-Québec had become one of the most reliable and efficient blood suppliers in the world.
First of all, he regained the public's trust, which had been seriously shaken by the blood-tainted scandal of the 1980's and 1990's.
As is well known, the national blood supply administered by the Transfusion Department of the Canadian Red Cross was contaminated with the immune deficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980's.
In response to this tragedy and the wave of public unwillingness, the Canadian government launched a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, to explain the circumstances leading up to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to ensure that such a disaster would not happen again.
While Judge Krever was delaying the report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélinea Committee took up this role.
Following the Gélineau and Krever report, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec, to supply Québec, and the Canadian Blood Company, to supply all provinces and both territories.
"When Héma-Québec started its operations in 1998, only 38 percent of the population still had confidence in the Quebec blood system", recalls Dr. Décary.
"The situation was depressing.
Through continuous efforts to improve the safety of blood products and continuous work in this area, we have regained public confidence over the years", he says, proudly adding that by the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population had trusted Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary does not forget that "trust is a very fragile thing".
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the prudent approach.
"We were seeing many cases of mad cow disease in Europe at the time, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease", says a woman who has led the company since it was founded in 1998.
"And we didn't know if this disease could be spread through blood.
We therefore based ourselves on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, namely that in cases where we do not know and where there is a serious disease at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterised by degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, preventive measures should be taken.
So in April 1999, we refused blood from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Then, a few years ago, it was safely proven that the disease is transmitted through blood.
So this episode showed us that it made sense to follow the precautionary principle".
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid assay (NAT) tests, which detect the presence of the virus itself in donor blood directly, rather than the presence of antibodies, on which previous tests were based.
NAT tests have shortened the silent period between the time a patient is infected and when our technicians can detect the first viruses in the blood, she explains.
We've managed to cut that down to less than a week.
We've significantly reduced the risk that some donors could be infected without us knowing and without us knowing.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
The risk of getting HIV-contaminated blood is now one in 12 million.
"In other words, before someone becomes infected with HIV, 12 million blood products will need to be distributed.
Since Héma-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products each year, it will be 24 years before the first case of HIV transmission through a blood product occurs.
I believe that today we can receive or prescribe transfusions of blood needed for healing in complete peace", says the head of Hema-Québec.
"The challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
We never know what pathogenic element might appear in the system.
Just last year, the chikungunya virus was discovered on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted through insect bites.
Constant vigilance is needed,' continues Dr Décary, stressing that in addition to safe supply, Héma-Québec must also expect sufficient supplies.
"Needs are growing as the population ages.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which on average consists of only 3% of eligible Quebecers".
Any healthy person who is at least 18 years old, who meets the eligibility criteria, but can only donate blood once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14 percent of people who offer blood are not accepted because they have, say, AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited a country where mudslides are common, they are excluded for a year.
"With this 3%, we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
The deficiencies are very rare.
However, the number of members in the donor network needs to be increased in proportion to their age and their inability to donate blood.
However, persuading people to donate blood is difficult, especially when it comes to keeping them and encouraging them to become regular donors.
Life is so unrestrained today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood", lamented Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, such as bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which is used almost exclusively for major burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Québec, which also runs the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
Once considered biomedical waste, the cord is teeming with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated the deposit of our thousandth cord blood sample to the bank a few weeks ago, and we expect to collect over a thousand a year.
Early next year we should start offering them for transplants", says Dr. Décary, who describes the cord blood collection program as a very popular one.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they do not have access to it", since Héma-Québec does not have the resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
