The "Plan Nord" is the fourth dimension of the "vision" the Prime Minister intends for Québec, the vision of the "new economic area", which includes the labour agreement with France, the convention between Canada and Europe and the agreement with Ontario.
Despite the fact that the opening of the North - the Northern Territory at the 49th parallel - has been mentioned by the Prime Minister in recent times, it has never been the subject of a presentation.
However, the Prime Minister limited himself to explaining why the North represents a "jewel with enormous potential", but did not give a timeline, the amount of investment, or a clear priority in future projects.
He mentioned at most several approaches to points which could be further divided: in particular hydroelectric power plants, forestry, but above all the mining sector, encouraged by the rapid growth of developing countries and the renewal of public infrastructure.
The North, according to Charest's calculations, contains "nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium, and even diamonds".
This "area twice the size of France is with us", is in Quebec.
And it's not just with us, it's in us", he stressed, as if to show that he was referring to a certain national founding myth.
Quebec was built largely in relation to the North, the Prime Minister pointed out: the Abitibi gold rush, Quebec engineering, James Bay.
"It's ours, it's our future", he added, after a theatrical pause to look at the huge map behind him.
The north, 70 per cent of Quebec, includes part of Labrador, which Quebec has always demanded, the premier said during a press conference.
"This is a traditional position that has been repeated by all previous governments.
There is one line of demarcation on which there is no convention for a long time, and if the opportunity arises, I will take up this position again on behalf of the Government,' he indicated.
Otherwise, "we also need to rethink our vision of the North in the context of climate change", he said, referring to the Northwest Passage, which will open year-round as a result of melting glaciers.
In this new geopolitical context, the Prime Minister feels that taking territory becomes a duty.
What about the inhabitants of the territory, the indigenous peoples and the Inuit?
The Prime Minister said that the Quebec government would be very attentive to them and that the project would be beneficial to them, especially the young.
Two former ministers from two different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (a former Pequino MP from Ungava), have already started negotiations with some 30 communities.
The action was taken by an interministerial committee chaired by Benoît Pelletier, in which Julie Boulet (Transport and Natural Resources) is an important member.
The Prime Minister does not rule out a big meeting, "not necessarily a summit", but a moment when "a common vision will be outlined".
The development of the North should, after all, be carried out in accordance with the principles of sustainable development.
The plan will be "collectively designed, structured and environmentally friendly", he promised.
Jean Charest described this "vision" as a seamless continuation of the vision of the liberal prime ministers who preceded him.
"Like the liberals before us, we have changed our mindsets to turn challenges into new opportunities for growth and development".
This was one of the still-shaky themes of the weekend, which began with a big cocktail on Friday to mark the 50th anniversary of Jean Lesage's rise to the party leadership.
