Opinions - Orwellian speech by Barrick Gold
In the September 17 issue of Le Devoir, a letter was printed by Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of Barrick Gold, a Canadian mining company.
With Orwellian logic, he confirms that the world's largest gold producer has launched a libel suit against three authors and a pathetic small publishing house in order to provoke a "transparent public debate" and is seeking six million dollars.
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge truth, especially in the case of defamation proceedings, but the law.
It's no surprise that Garver completely skips that crucial distinction.
Or is the best way for Barrick Gold to drive public debate, to bankrupt anyone who dares to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of Noir Canada will be forced to spend considerable sums to prepare to defend and fight a highly uneven battle with an army of lawyers backed by the almost bottomless pockets of the mining companies.
The tactics in these unbalanced fights, moreover, often consist in the destruction of the defendants in order to enforce a conciliation procedure that will silence the opposing side and, moreover, frighten anyone who dares to enter into the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, they should have presented their view of the matter to the public.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada, the debate is normally about the exchange of ideas, not the lashing of a club.
So it was not enough for the mining companies to open their books, their documentation and to create a real debate through newspapers, media, publications and funding independent scientific teams that could shed light on the whole thing.
Barrick Gold, however, seems to have no confidence in public opinion and is vehemently rejecting petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand "public debate" and at the same time despise the views of the same public?
It seems that in the Vice President's world, that word refers only to the well-paid lawyers, not all Canadians; that's a rather narrow definition of the term.
In a democracy, even the disrespectful have a say.
Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - that the public supporting the writers and publishers of Noir Canada is doing so primarily because it rejects the brutal ways of the mining company.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and judge the case, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not in what many perceive as a prosecution in which the defendant is to be gagged (in its "public debate" prosecution, by the way, Barrick has just issued an official appeal to Noir Canada to inform them officially to stop using the term...).
Apart from Garver's surreal speech, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct assault on the university's freedom of inquiry and search for truth, which is essential to any democratic society.
It generally denies the right to cite reliable sources and to debate facts and interpretations that are the very basis of intellectual activity.
If it is impossible in a country like Canada to study and discuss topics that are not liked by the wealthy corporations of this world without being subjected to repeated prosecution, who else will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, they could have created one if they followed the scientific standards that Noir Canada authors use.
He has a right to an answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debate and disagreement and to resolve conflict.
Barrick Gold's outrageous lawsuit clearly shows that despite what it claims, it has no desire to conduct a transparent debate.
It's a loss for the academic world, as well as for the public debate in Canada, and it's time for governments to put in place measures to limit this type of unwarranted prosecution.
The Wall Street bailout operation - Democrats and Republicans getting along
The Bush administration and members of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached agreement yesterday on the biggest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
A new version of the plan to use $700 billion to stem the financial crisis that has plagued Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both houses of Congress.
In particular, it provides for: better control by elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms to ensure repayment of public money deposited, new measures to capture the number of houses seized for non-payment and the right to monitor the salaries paid to executives of rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican negotiating delegate Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news minutes after midnight yesterday, after a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We've made great strides and we've reached an agreement that will work in the markets", said Henry Paulson, a spokesman for the Bush administration.
"Everything was done to keep the real economy and the average American safe from the crisis that's going on on Wall Street", the Democrat explained.
"This is the bottom line: If we don't do this, the trauma, chaos and disruption to the daily lives of Americans will be enormous", said Republican Judd Gregg.
Over the last few hours, negotiations have been running at full speed, fearing the effect of further failure on investors' mood.
The time limit was the markets opening this morning.
Both candidates for the US presidency were later invited to negotiate and both expressed themselves rather in favour of an agreement, without failing to express their dissatisfaction with the need to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama credited the amendment to the agreement with some measures, especially one aimed at allowing homeowners to keep their homes and a wage measure for government-backed workers.
"When we ask taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is no point in congratulating ourselves.
But these measures are necessary", he explained on television.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, when asked by another station if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so".
"The rough lines I've read [suggest] that this is something we're all going to have to digest and move on from.
To choose inaction is simply unacceptable", he said.
The goal of the $700 billion plan is to buy back with taxpayer money the dubious claims and risky and unsold assets of American financial institutions.
The plan follows a 14-month crisis triggered by the bursting of a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of subprime mortgages, then moved to other, more extensive forms of credit (PCAA), resulting in cash freezes and the break-up of banks and financial institutions.
The failure of the first draft of the agreement last week is the fault of the Republican lawmakers.
Since the Democrats have agreed that some of the toxic assets of troubled companies will be guaranteed by the government, not bought, there is a belief that the deadlock is set.
In an effort to reconcile the conflicting views in Congress, a provision was attached providing that the government could introduce new fees to help it recover its deposit if it had to take losses as a result of the program for five years.
The new plan includes a first deposit of $250 billion, to which an additional $100 billion may be added if the president deems it necessary.
The deposit of another 350 billion should be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get shares in the rescued companies, which will pay him dividends if they make a profit, and which he can resell when it's over.
The Federal Government will be able to delay the procedures for the seizure of real estate linked to the loans covered by the plan, as well as to set limits on the amount of valuation and compensation paid to the executives of the affected companies.
The plan's authors would like to put it to a vote in the House today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts made, it's not yet certain that their plan will go green.
Yesterday, there was a continuing backlash against the bill from both the Republican and Democratic parties.
"It's clear that Washington can't hear you", said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, addressing voters.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But taxpayer profits are not the answer".
Democratic Representative Brad Sherman, moderator of a congressional group nicknamed the "Committee of Skeptics", presents the matter differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred respected economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us: we ask Congress not to rush too much and to consider carefully which way to go", he declared yesterday.
At the same time, the crisis in Europe has been reaffirmed as a global crisis.
Following the end of the extraordinary meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for EUR 11,2 billion (USD 16,3 billion).
The intervention of the Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from the purchase of its competitor, which has been on the verge of collapse since losing EUR 2 billion (USD 2,9 billion) in the wake of the risky mortgage crisis in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people, is among the 20 largest European banks and among the 10 largest insurance companies.
"We will not lose this money", said the Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
"In return, we get voting rights in the bank and influence.
This is what the landlords and households can appreciate in these uncertain times".
On the other side of the Channel, meanwhile, the British government seems to have begun the nationalisation of another bank affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was to take over all existing loans from Bradford and Bringley, of which more than 41 billion ($75.5 billion) were for the purchase of real estate.
According to its announcement yesterday, the Spanish bank Santander is buying the branches and accounts of the British bank's clients.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock to be nationalised by the British government since the start of the financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of socially engaged icons
His beauty with blue eyes long represented his strength, according to others, weakness.
Has this American actor with a charming smile escaped from narcissism?
Yes and no.
The shyness, sensitivity and relentless talent that were his own also kept him from the power category that makes for true stars.
But what a long-distance runner he was!
Paul Newman died Friday at the age of 83 at his Connecticut ranch of lung cancer and remains one of the last icons of the fat years of American cinema.
Less spectacular than Brando, to whom he was similar and long a sort of rival on the screen, Newman was a more cautious actor, certainly fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the breakdown of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often produces beautiful children.
Born in Ohio in 1925, his father was German-Jewish and his mother was of Hungarian origin.
From these European roots, one of the great faces of the American dream was born.
Without the exaggerated ego, which is the last mark of quality.
Because he was the one who saw this whole country in love with the self-made man, a war veteran in the Pacific, wounded in battle, who studied acting at Yale in the early '50s, then attended the New York Actor's Studio and celebrated his triumph in theater, television and soon in film.
The same civil rights activist was also a race car driver who finished second in the 1979 24 Hours of Le Mans, and a sex symbol, despite having been a model couple with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
And with it go the shadowy places of this hidden, discreet, socially engaged star, allergic to the whimsy of show business itself, which will forever remain somewhat mysterious.
A decent man, in the noblest sense of the word.
Paul Newman's departure this weekend has left film lovers dizzy as his great roles compete on the black screen of memories.
It is followed by more than half a century of ever-changing American seventh art.
The memory re-emerges as the charming cowboy from Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), a young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on a Hot Tin Roof, a 1958 Tennessee Williams adaptation.
From a time not so long ago (1990) we remember his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled in his old age by a marriage that failed to meet all expectations.
So many other Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
Boxer Rocky Graziano, the abusive, violent, unforgettable delinquent from Robert Wise's Somebody Up There Likes Me, a role originally intended for James Dean, assumed after his death, which in 1956 brought Newman into the limelight.
The sympathetic gangster in the absolutely brilliant The Sting, Oscar for best picture in 1973.
The bitter and vengeful pool player in Robert Rosen's stunning The Hustler (1961), the same character he portrayed in Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, which earned him his only Oscar nomination in 1987 out of seven.
This face wandering through the ages, that was him.
And then there's him.
His career is a race between different eras.
Young people know him best for his iconic Slap Shot George Roy Hill (1977) as Reggie Dunlop, an unconventional hockey coach.
Fans met him again in 1994 at The Hudsucker Proxy of the Coen brothers.
He then closed his career by playing the godfather of the Irish Mafia in Sam Mendes' Road to Perdition in 2003.
Unlike several film legends who left the business fairly early, Newman remained in the business long after he denounced Hollywood for its glitz, pomp and concession.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier, not without humor, considered it "a lively challenge to underplaying", judging that he pushed too hard in his performances.
For the handsome Paul Newman, whose roles came as a surprise, the profession was not always so tender.
But he played first lovers less often than outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, thugs and desperate people, whose downfall and rebellion were reflected in his perfect features.
As a director, Newman has revealed the little-known sides of his shy sensibilities.
His 1968 film Rachel, Rachel (based on a novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), starring his wife Joanne Woodward, provides a sensitive portrait of a woman full of melancholy.
He dedicated the 1984 film Harry and Son to his son Scott, who died of a drug overdose, a work full of shame and sadness.
In the tribute to Newman yesterday, his great friend and former comrade Robert Redford (who co-starred in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) lamented, "His presence has made my life and this country better".
Generosity, love of life, such are the chief qualities of a dead actor.
Aside from his legendary career, he's also a great civil rights activist, environmentalist, independent filmmaker, and opponent of Hollywood's decline.
We used to see his image on vinegar bottles, sauces, cookies and other foods, which might seem rather unpleasant, although at first it was a gag.
However, the proceeds from the sale went to his Foundation for a Troubled Childhood.
So, rather than be swayed by fame, Newman engaged in the company until the last moment.
He left a letter to his five daughters that contained the following words: "Your father was always, and to the end, grateful to his happy planet.
It was an honor to be here".
And it was an honor to follow the career of such a visionary and generous American artist.
And besides, after all, a model citizen.
What was produced at the Zuschlag & Co. invoice factory?
Soon, on October 8, the trial of János Zuschlag and his associates will begin.
The politician and his associates are charged with fraud, including forgery of documents, as well as with long-term and systematic criminal activities by a criminal organisation, which have caused exceptionally significant damage.
According to the prosecutor's office, they used the money obtained in public tenders for their own purposes and often used fictitious invoices to prove the completion of their tasks.
The money from the state and local authorities - a total of approximately 65 million forints - went partly to the treasury of Fiatal Baloldal, partly to the pockets of individuals.
The method also reported by the investigating authority was that the money obtained in the public tenders was collected on the basis of invoices for which there was no real consideration and the undertakings accepted by the association were never received.
According to the prosecution, a large portion of the invoices were counterfeit.
The forms for these invoices came from the market in Józsefváros, the circular stamp was made in Kiskunhalasi.
The names of the companies on which invoices are to be issued were decided, inter alia, on the roundabout on the northern shore of Balaton, which István Lados sent János Zuschlag to.
According to his testimony, the first appointment was to look at boarding houses and restaurants.
In those documents, he requested accounts for his consumption, the model of which was then used to produce invoices submitted in the context of public tenders organised by, inter alia, the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs and the Metropolitan Government.
The invoices were mostly issued by István Lados and his partner András Őr, who, according to our information, wrote the most frequent reports needed to obtain subsidies.
On his "study trip", Lados spotted a cellar.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and its partners in 2003, this catering establishment provided catering for a group of 90 members of Biztos Pont.
However, the company's manager claimed that this large number of people could not fit into the facility at once.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 by the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later by Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért, was riddled with errors of form and content.
The boarding house in Badacsonytomaji had only three rooms, and more than ten people could not sleep in it one night, yet the bill listed 130 guests.
The imaginative printing presses, however, went too far when they listed on the documents a company also involved in the hospitality industry, Pigal s.r.o., whose accounts, according to the information provided to the Public Prosecutor's Office, did not even contain documents bearing the names Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
The head of Győző Farkas told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the prosecutor's office and shown the invoices, he knew immediately that they were false documents.
"Our company name and tax number were on the wrong stamp".
He added that, apart from the formalities, the fact that according to the invoice, they accommodated 100 people was also not acceptable, because they only have 11 rooms that do not have such a large capacity.
In addition, the invoice also stated the catering, and their restaurant has not been operating for a long time.
The enthusiastic invoice makers were not even convinced that the prominent Budapest travel agency was organising only international trips, and they foolishly referred to the cash-paid invoice, which was also inconsistent with the firm's invoicing practice, as a travel agency service in Hungary.
Moreover, as it emerged during the investigation, VAT was also mentioned in the document, although the organisation of trips to countries outside the European Union was exempt from VAT.
Four documents issued by Hotel Révfülöp s.r.o. to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation did not include the amount of VAT, since the company's activities were not subject to the 25% VAT, but to the 15% VAT, and the hotel employees only issued printed invoices, but the invoice was handwritten.
Furthermore, the 'issuers' corrupted the invoice, for example by referring to one company as having carried out, as revealed by the prosecutor's investigation, a road haulage activity which the company, which was originally based on investment advice, did not carry out.
The fact that invoices issued by the Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért foundation and by the XXI Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Pont Biztos associations are false was also revealed due to formal discrepancies - the incorrect invoice format and the false stamp.
As in the case of Ravenna k.s. or the Kunfehérto Sports Camp, whose representatives denied that they had issued the invoices.
The Commission notes that the Commission has not yet established the existence of a market economy operator in the Netherlands, which is not a market economy operator.
They were knowingly issuing invoices
The second group of invoicers are those who knew they were to issue a fictitious invoice.
The Esély Budapestért Foundation has issued bills for approximately four million forints to the Harmadik Évezredért Foundation at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Socialisták organization.
The Director of Collab s.r.o. was, according to the indictment, forced to issue a fictitious account by one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi.
Zuschlag and its partners were also cooperated with by Biogate s.r.o., currently in liquidation, which in 2003 provided the Jobb Jövőért Foundation and the Atlasz and Vörösfenyő associations with invoices worth approximately HUF 5 million, which were not in the form of actual economic activity.
Nor did the movement of money, because the invoices created were later cancelled, which, of course, the organizations forgot to mention in their documents.
The other group of invoicing firms include those that had ties to the defendants.
For example, Ivan Kubatov was the authorised representative of the Ukrainian manager of Delta Trió s.r.o., a company involved in the trading of fuels and motor vehicles, based in Budapest, but the company is not located there.
The company immediately issued several invoices for the sale of computing equipment worth approximately HUF 18 million in October, November and December 2005.
According to the information found by the investigation, these invoices were purchased by Cash Investment s.r.o. of Kiskunhalas, which was in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The manager of this company was a Romanian man, to whom he was to deliver documents concerning the company also belonging to Ivan Kubatov from 2002 to 2005.
As we know, during the investigation Kubatov admitted that he issued invoices on behalf of the company to the associations Atlas, Hoppá and the foundations Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért and that he himself received their countervalue.
At the request of Ivan Kubatov, the Romanian masons founded Fa-Bani Jos Faipari s.r.o. and Jos-Investment k.s.
In fact, none of the firms were working, according to the defendant, because they were not employed.
Nevertheless, the companies were to his advantage, since at the request of the co-defendant, Zsolt Szente, who also drew up their articles of association, he issued invoices on behalf of the company to the associations Atlasz and Y-Generáció, which were linked to Zuschlag.
On behalf of Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, Kubatov has issued a total of 15 invoices worth HUF 14,2 million to the organisations.
The prosecutor's office determined that Kubatov received 10 percent of the invoice and VAT amounts.
To issue fictitious invoices, this time for the selection procedure for Biztos Pont, the man also used the company Szi-Beri k. t.
In January 2006, the Y-Generáció and Szövetség and Modern Magyarországért associations submitted their proposals to the public competition of the Mihálye Táncsicse Foundation (TMA), a public benefit organisation of the Socialist Party.
They each received 500 000 forints, but did not spend the sums on the objectives set out in the proposals.
To keep this from becoming apparent, TMA submitted five fictitious invoices from Works Team s.r.o.
These invoices were found during a home search in Árpád Kemecsei's office at the Ministry of Education.
During the hearing, some of the defendants will probably describe the process of producing the invoices, as they did at the prosecutor's office.
What might be interesting is if the main defendant, János Zuschlag, decides to reveal everything himself.
His testimony so far has been rather vague, and although he has promised several times to give a full account, he has not done so.
The question is, is it in his interest - in exchange for paying a large part of the damage, 50 million forints, maybe the socialists have made a deal with him and Zusi will take it upon himself.
He could have been offended, as his requests for a reduction in his detention, namely to house arrest, have so far remained unanswered.
While economic offenders who have committed much more damage and have not yet recovered can walk around freely or at least wait for the end of the proceedings against them in their homes, he does not have that option.
The psychology of trump: why are we spending more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overvalue goods.
The neurological and economic basis for this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior has been uncovered by researchers at New York University's Department of Neuroscience and Economics.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people don't want to fall behind in an eBay-style auction, so they'd rather pay too high a price.
Researchers have been trying to map the pattern of this "game" in the nervous system by experimental auction.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group participated in a playful auction, and the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method was used to examine the active areas of the subjects' brains.
In both games, participants could win money, but in the auction game, an important element of which is to beat the other side, a whole under the cerebral cortex called the striatum became activated when losing.
This brain region plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system, among many other functions.
The researchers therefore consider that the price screening can be explained by the attempt to avoid a sharp reaction of the striates.
To support their theory, members of the research team of economists conducted a financial cross-sectional study.
Three groups bid against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made bets.
Additionally, members of the other group were promised an additional $15 in prize money if they came out on top.
The third group received $15 before the auction, but if they lost, they lost that money too.
So the difference between the two groups was that one group was emphasized as winning and the other as losing.
However, members of the "playing against" group were willing to go higher than those in the "winning" and "control" groups, confirming the neurological hypothesis.
"These results cannot be derived from any pre-existing economic theory.
They have explained the phenomena observed in auctions of the joy of winning and the avoidance of risk.
Neurological imaging has helped us to resolve the discrepancy between these two theories, so that we have now come to a third explanation", says Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: When to See a Doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infections, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is listed as a leading cause of death.
The number of domestic hepatitis cases is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 of them are treated, because the sick often do not know they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a collective term for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
They have many similarities in their symptoms, with hepatitis and jaundice being the hallmarks, but the pathogens and the diseases they cause are different.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses are spread in two main ways: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e. g. infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses in the blood and body fluids (sperm, faecal secretions, saliva).
Travellers should in any case protect themselves by vaccinating against virus A and B, there is no vaccine against virus type C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after ingestion of infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal pain, vomiting.
Then the skin and eye whites become yellow, the stool lightened, and the urine darkened.
Each year, a million people worldwide die from the more serious form of the disease, liver cancer and cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected persons is receiving medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver or liver cancer.
Most people who are infected do not know they have the disease, and the virus is so insidious that it destroys liver cells that in many cases the first symptoms do not appear until 20 or 30 years later.
Therefore, early prevention, regular detection, is very important.
Three groups have a much higher than average incidence of the disease: people who received blood transfusions before 1991, drug users, and people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated worldwide number of individuals infected with chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease can be detected by routine laboratory tests, a person should consult his or her physician if any symptoms of unknown origin are noticed.
If detected early, the disease is curable, the virus can be removed from the body, preventing infection and preventing cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first celebrated worldwide in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
It aims to raise awareness of chronic hepatitis caused by these viruses, the causes of its occurrence and the importance of early detection.
Who believes in God doesn't feel this pain?
According to recent research, belief in God acts as a kind of analgesic that may have eased death even for Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment to investigate how belief in a god affects a person's perception of pain, reports Britain's Telegraph.
In a rather bizarre study, 12 Catholics and an equal number of atheists were subjected to electric shocks while all were watching a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
The results showed that Catholics were able to rule out much of the pain.
By examining the human brain in detail, it was also shown that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
The research is the first in a series of studies involving academics as well as scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university.
The test was carried out by attaching a spark device to the left hand of the subject, which gave electric shocks.
The researchers asked the participants to look intently at two paintings: Sassoferrato's 17th-century Virgin Mary and Leonardo da Vinci's 15th-century Lady with a Border.
The authors of the study hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke a certain state of devotion in the faithful, whereas the da Vinci painting was chosen because it was not very different from the first and, according to them, had a calming effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, during which time they received 20 electric shocks in four successive sessions, while they separately viewed an image with a religious or general theme.
Catholics reported that looking at the Virgin Mary made them feel "safe", as if they were "taken care of", and "calmed down, filled with peace".
When viewing a religious painting, they reported feeling 12 percent less pain than when they were in front of a Leonardo.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who was involved in the study, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any powerful image, even for atheists, just by finding the right photograph.
"We have to find an image that they will see very positively, from the perspective of a mother or a father", said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"Practice of faith should change, and in many cases will change, our personality", Wright added.
After such brilliant results, it's only a question of what effect would it have on the regulation of the pain of the faithful if they were shown a Madonna by Leonardo or a painter of similar calibre.
Would a good view of the Virgin Mary mean even better results?
You are what you share
On its tenth birthday, Google may declare that people can find it in their pocket at least as well as in the sky above them; they know where they've been on vacation, what expert investigations they're going to, and what they're interested in.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's executives, that's still not enough.
But for the skeptics who parallel Orwellian dark vision, they're not exactly clear about the very nature of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main goal is to collect even more personal information about users, which is necessary if the founders of Google are to stick to their original intention: "Let's organize all the information in the world!"
According to a Google official, after ten years of global work, the company is only at the beginning of its work with all the information.
When asked what will happen in five years, Schmidt said he would like Google to be able to answer questions like, "What should I do tomorrow?" or "What kind of job would I be doing?" - seemingly simple questions, but the software won't be able to answer until it knows enough about the users.
Not all Internet users are well aware that the search terms are captured precisely during the Internet search, as well as the IP address from which the search was made and the pages to which the searchers have moved.
For example, with Personalized Search, launched two years ago, users can save their browsing history, look back at what they searched for and clicked on, and in the long term generate findings that are much more tailored to them - the same logic will be used for Recommendations, whereby the system will offer us products and services based on previously mentioned and saved preferences.
What if my data is used against me, what if someone looks at what I'm doing? ask users who are afraid to look at Google's data monopoly.
In most cases, the extent of the potential power represented by the company is more alarming, the backlash does not provoke guilt, fear of punishment, a desire for freedom or even rebellion against power in Internet users.
However, it is a confirmed fact that all search terms are not only captured but can also be disclosed to third parties in justified cases, in such legal cases the privacy rights of Internet users are not protected.
Perhaps the most well-known recent example was the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google provided the Brazilian government with information that allowed the identification of pedophiles from the Orkut community sites it set up.
However, privacy-conscious netizens were relieved in May when the company, in partnership with the electronic rights group EFF, successfully proved its case against the FBI: Google must not be forced by any article of the Constitution to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI in the future.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully fought off nearly 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms that it obtained by appealing to the strengthening of the Child Protection Act passed years ago, yet it failed to get individual user search lists, or complete lists of websites and keywords, covering a two-month period.)
The view of Google is quite contradictory: it is being whipped by those who fear giving their personal data because they feel that their private sphere and private life will be compromised by starting to use Google services, and they are rebelling against it with the kind of revolt that belongs to multinational companies with a conservative image.
And meanwhile, the American geek culture and its wild offshoot, the enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users, emerging in many countries, see in him a new generation of big business, "the corporation that's now busting", as opposed to its rival Microsoft, which is considered to be the world's conqueror because of Windows, however both are fighting for the same goals.
This may be because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not require users to provide an identification code or pay for its applications; the open, free and constantly fresh source of information and software package seems much more accessible, youthful, "cooler" than the official software giant's practice.
But it could also be because geeks have a very good understanding of the very problematic relationship between the Internet and privacy rights, which has brought about one of the most cliched keywords of recent years: Web 2.0.
Because Web 2.0 is nothing more than collaboration, about intentionally leaving behind a footprint and using the channels of communication that we have, and while the scope is different in everyone, the essence is the same: we show up.
The average young person can have a profile on several community sites, from Facebook to Xang, which he can easily connect to other services, such as Twitter or the last.fm app, which records the music he listens to, and then he can connect to navigation systems like FriendFeed or Blip.fm, and he can also write a blog, where his latest photo gallery will automatically appear, which he stores on Flickru or Picase.
We can read about many examples of how it shines through: a friend in the morning can easily tell who her funny boyfriend spent the evening with by looking at a flood of photos of their mutual friends, or a company can fire an employee just because he writes his honest opinion about senior management on its blog: one thing is certain, the concept of privacy has been completely reassessed today.
The online life is what you show up to be, so we could define the basic thesis behind the behavior of today's youth.
And anyone who wants to keep something secret or at least avoid Google's monopoly has a choice (starting with Scroogl, who uses Google's search engine but intentionally leaves no trace).
For example, a significant number of people don't register on community sites on purpose, so they can't be found. Google's online apps from text editor to photo editor to news portal can be swapped for alternative versions that aren't connected to the giant server park and that don't build the best possible profile of us.
Public opinion is not too secretive about waiting for Google to show its teeth.
At its current value, the company is worth $156 billion more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion), or Coca-Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense ad space is threatening the investment of advertising agencies, and the services being introduced at an ever-accelerating pace are seriously disrupting not only Microsoft but also numerous other software designers.
However, critics also find counter-points that are disturbing: for example, the top management completely rejected the protests of employees after doubling the company's tuition fees, the arbitrary frequency of the daily meals for employees was too expensive according to the management of the company, all of which is lost alongside the fact that Google bowed to the Chinese government back in 2006 and, according to their agreement, filters out any findings that are in the best interest of the Chinese regime.
One of the company's internal rules is that it never announces new services in advance until they are ready to be used, but what is certain is that the problems expected in the months and years ahead could be stirring the world in new places: while some believe that Google's project to scan and archive books and magazines is gaining such scale that the company will soon have to deal with the US Supreme Court, others are terrified of its health system, in which we can build our own complete health profile with previous findings, doctors and problems.
The fact that Google is compiling a genetic database can then serve as a good starting point for the next generation of science fiction writers, Cory Doctorow's famous novel "Scroogled" describes with Orwellian reminiscences a future in which humans can be intimidatingly close to each other only with the help of Google data.
The double murderer from Oz was helped to remove the tracks by two teenagers
Two teenagers were questioned by police in the case of a double murder in Ózd, and were suspected of helping to remove traces of the crime, a spokesman for the Borsod County Police Department said on Tuesday.
The individuals who were suspected of the activity have confessed and are currently charged with aiding and abetting.
Both juveniles, according to MTI, two girls, are on the loose.
Aiding and abetting a crime is punishable by up to five years in prison.
The suspect in the double murder in Ozd, a 23-year-old local man, was taken into custody on Sunday.
He's a suspect in a premeditated multiple homicide for obvious reasons.
During the investigation, it was revealed that a 23-year-old man owed a larger amount to a 53-year-old man.
The suspect refused to pay his debt, so he lured his creditor into a factory in Ozd last Wednesday, killing first a man and then his nine-year-old daughter.
According to MTI, the young man had prepared for the crime in advance, as evidenced by the fact that he committed the murder with a weapon hidden at the scene.
The weapon and the circumstances of its use are being investigated by the police with the involvement of experts.
The Warsaw Stock Exchange has made an offer to buy the Prague Stock Exchange
Two hundred million euros - approximately five billion CZK - was offered by the Warsaw Stock Exchange for the purchase of a 100% stake in the Prague Stock Exchange.
Ludwik Sobolewski, chairman of the Warsaw Stock Exchange, confirmed the offer made by the Polish side despite the fact that the Czechs had already excluded the Warsaw Stock Exchange from the circle of possible new owners of the Prague Stock Exchange.
The reason is that the Warsaw Stock Exchange is owned by the state.
99 percent of the shares are in the hands of the Polish state, which wishes to sell 60 percent of the securities in a few months.
According to the Czech economic daily E15, the Polish bid represents the highest amount ever offered to a candidate for the Prague stock exchange.
According to the Czech newspapers, the bids have so far been submitted by the Vienna Stock Exchange, the transatlantic stock exchange Nasdaq, the New York Stock Exchange, the London Stock Exchange and Deutsche Börse.
