A smart car simulates the flight of a bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop collision-preventing technologies if not by mimicking obstacle detectors found in the natural world?
Like with bees.
The initial strategic idea for the surprising project, presented at the CEATEC trade fair in Japan, was inspired by Nissan's engineers, bees, to build a new generation of crash-prevention systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has designed the BR23C biomimetic robotic control system, a robotic minicar that is equipped with bee characteristics, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
"During flight, each bee creates its own personal oval-shaped space, which is actually very similar to our safety protective packaging", explained Kazuhiro Doi, the brand's general manager for technology PR and R&D, at the exhibition.
Importantly, the compound eyes allow the bees to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees.
To replicate the function of the compound eye, engineers came up with the idea of a laser telescope.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 metres in front of the BR23C in a 180° field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor which is immediately converted into a collision avoidance operation.
The obstacle is detected within a fraction of a second, then the robotic car begins to mimic the bee's movements and, by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to avoid a collision, immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this maneuver is done in a completely instinctive manner.
"Without this, the robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
They must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology suits the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety shield, within which collision is currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process has to reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must not take more than a blink of an eye.
But unlike bees, this movement cannot be upward, downward, or angular, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be turned.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to the bees by avoiding, the robot car was limited to rotating, accelerating and decelerating.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer life than the lithium-ion variants.
Ando says it's instinctive, intelligent reaction that matters, not the ability to process, much less store data.
This mechanism shall only process and respond to a few incoming signals per second.
It does not need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it only uses memory of a few kilobytes at a time.
It doesn't need a gigabyte or a megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in developing an immediate avoidance technology that Nissan estimates could be in production cars within 10 years.
Another application may be to connect the unit to the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the motorist to the specified final destination after avoiding obstacles in the way.
