The $700 billion economic rescue package, to be split into several installments, aimed at buying back bad loans from banks, is already in writing.
Half of the amount will be used in the first round.
After further talks, which ended after midnight on Saturday, congressional officials reached an agreement in days of debate on a $700 billion bailout package, Reuters reported.
"We've made significant progress", announced Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic speaker of the House of Representatives, who said that all that remains is to write a deal.
The compromise package was also supported by both presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain.
The result of the compromise, said Henry Paulson, the Chancellor of the Exchequer: "The programme will work and be effective, but further steps need to be taken".
The paper version of the package was released ahead of the opening of Asian markets on Sunday at 8 p.m. Washington time (i.e. Monday at 2 a.m. Central European time), but it did not cause any particular upturn on the stock exchanges.
The bill, known as the 2008 Emergency Economic Stabilization Act, which is to establish the program, will be voted on Monday first in the House of Representatives, then in the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi on Saturday night, and then news of the deal was welcomed at the White House.
"We are pleased with the progress made tonight and appreciate the efforts of both sides to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy", White House spokesman Tony Fratto said.
The program is different from the original proposal of the Bush administration, which was to spend a total of $700 billion on the purchase of substandard mortgage-backed securities.
Now, it's possible to spend up to half of the $700 billion in the first round, with the $250 billion going to be used immediately after the expected Congressional vote on Monday, and the Treasury Department will use it to buy mortgage-backed securities that are rated as substandard, with the fate of the remaining $100 billion then being decided by the president.
The program will be overseen by a special committee, including the chairman of the Federal Reserve.
The second half of the $700 billion will depend on the next congressional decision.
The Ministry of Finance may, within the meaning of the law, apply a combined tactic: it may simultaneously buy back bad loans, mortgages and securities backed by mortgages, or other 'toxic' loans.
The buyback can be done through auctions or directly, the competent officials of the Ministry have informed.
The legal provision will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance scheme whereby the Ministry of Finance will provide them with a guarantee for the funds constituting a cause of concern, for which the companies will pay a price corresponding to the amount of the expected losses.
As Henry Paulson said, the law provides the means to spend up to $700 billion to meet the urgent needs of the U.S. financial system, whether it be to purchase large amounts of bad assets, insure them, or prevent the systemic risk of the collapse of one of the big financial institutions.
"We will take the necessary steps to be ready to introduce the law as soon as it is signed", he added.
Bank bosses who are in trouble and waiting for the government to help them can, on the other hand, count on the government to reduce their severance pay - simply called "the golden parachute" in overseas slang.
The limitation of their remuneration will only occur in certain cases, and will depend on the type of aid granted by the Ministry.
The restriction essentially means that if the Ministry buys through the auction, the gold parachutes will be taxed unless the fallen bank directors are sent straight to retirement.
In the case of direct repurchase of bad loans, the government will act aggressively to ensure that the money for management is not overspent.
It should be added that the existing gold parachute contracts will not be changed, the restriction only applies to new contracts, which is intended to be a further incentive to participate in the programme.
"This is the first time in American history that a law will impose a limit on the compensation of CEOs", commented House Financial Services Committee Chairman Barney Frank, a Democrat.
In addition, the State will have the right to acquire a stake in the participating banks, thus reducing the risk for taxpayers, who can profit from the transaction once the economy and the rescued bank are back on their feet.
The draft plan states that over the next five years, the president must submit to Congress a proposal to determine how taxpayers can recover their expected losses from the financial sector.
Of course, there were also voices of doubt on both sides of the plan.
"This is not what the American people asked us to do, because this is not going to protect taxpayer dollars", declared Republican Congressman Darrell Issa of California.
His Ohio Democrat colleague Mary Kaptur believes that the passage of the ordinance was pushed by the very people responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continued to rise
Domestic sales prices in industry increased in August 2008 by 0,1% compared to the previous month and by 12,9% compared to August 2007, the Central Statistical Office reported.
Export sales prices of the industry were 1,1% higher compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3,9% year on year.
As a result of the changes in domestic and export prices, the prices of the industry were higher by 0,7% compared to the previous month, rising by 3,2% year on year.
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased only marginally, by 0,1%, compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing sectors also increased slightly, by 0,1% compared to July.
The largest price increases took place in August 2008 in the leather and footwear sector (2,8%) mainly due to the monthly price increases in the poultry and saddlery sector of 4,6% and footwear by 2,5% respectively.
The higher price level of plastics and chemicals has led to a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical materials and products industry (1,6 per cent).
The price decrease was recorded in the oil processing sector (1,4%) and in the electrical machinery and equipment manufacturing sector (0,9%), as well as, to a minimal extent, in the wood processing sector (0,1%).
Prices in the paper industry and publishing and printing activities remained unchanged.
In the other sectors of the manufacturing industry, we have measured price increases in the range of 0,2 to 0,9%.
In the electricity, gas and water sectors, which are important in domestic industry, prices rose by 0.3% in August, mainly due to the continuing effect of the officially announced increase in gas prices since 1 July.
In the 12-month comparison of domestic sales in the different sectors of the manufacturing industry, the highest price increase was recorded in the specialised sector of oil processing (32,4%).
The steel-processing sector recorded a price increase of 13,2%, followed by a price increase of 11% in the food, beverage and tobacco sector, which is the most important.
The decrease in prices was recorded in the textile and textile products industries (2,5%) and in the electrical machinery and equipment industries (0,3%).
In the other manufacturing sectors, the price growth rate ranged between 0,6% and 9,1%.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing sector increased by 10,2% over the previous year.
Prices in the electricity, gas and water production and distribution sectors were higher than the previous year by 18,7%.
In terms of industry focus, the highest monthly price increase in August was recorded in domestic sales (0.7%) in the sectors involved in the production of tangible assets.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0,3%, while in the energy and manufacturing sectors, prices remained unchanged compared to the previous month.
The largest increase in prices compared to the same month of the previous year was observed in August 2008 in the energy processing and downstream sectors (16,8%).
In the consumer goods sectors, we have seen a price increase of 6.8%, while in the material assets sector, prices fell by 1.4%.
Export sales prices of industrial products measured in forints increased by 1,1% in August compared to the previous month, falling by 3,9% over the same period.
Our domestic currency weakened by 1.7% against the euro, by 7.1% against the dollar, and by 7.5% against the euro and 15.9% against the dollar in one month compared with August 2007.
