The European Summit on Equality, which this year will be hosted by France, the current EU Presidency, has begun in Paris.
In her message to the plenary, Lívia Járóková, MEP for the Fidesz party, as one of the main speakers of the expert debate, drew attention to segregation in education, which is one of the most serious injustices affecting Roma children and the most serious obstacle to their implementation.
The summit was opened by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Labour and Social Affairs, on behalf of the French Presidency, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
The meeting was attended by representatives of governments, European social partners, the most important European rights organisations and civil society organisations active in the field of equal opportunities.
According to the press office of the Fidesz group of MEPs, Járóková pointed out that, in addition to discrimination in recruitment, the Roma are excluded from the European labour market mainly because of their low education.
"The vast majority of young Roma do not have a secondary education and, due to the poor quality of primary education, only a small proportion of them can reach a higher level of education".
Járóková further stressed that education as a fundamental human right has a key role in the implementation of other human rights.
Investing in early education for Roma children can boost the economies of the EU Member States.
The Commission is also proposing to extend the scope of the EU's support for the fight against corruption.
The earlier a Roma student starts school, the better chance he or she has of becoming a productive member of the labour market; through income taxes and excise duties, they contribute to the national budget.
'It is the right of Roma to have citizenship in the European Union to ensure their right to quality education and to guarantee the elimination of their poor quality and segregated education,' emphasised Lívia Járóková.
The Commission's proposal for a directive on the protection of employees from the risks related to the use of certain dangerous substances and preparations is based on the principle that the protection of employees from the risks related to the use of certain dangerous substances is ensured by the directive.
'The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be broken, and Roma children must be given the opportunities afforded by democracy so that they can participate as full citizens in the future of Europe,' Járóková demanded.
The European Year of Equal Opportunities guarantees everyone the aim of the European Equality Summit, held annually since last year's meeting in Berlin, to provide a separate forum to help achieve the equality and elimination of discrimination objectives set at European and national level.
