Prolonged listening to loud music and the use of portable musical instruments such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
According to the Communication from the European Commission published today, which quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee on the health risks recently identified (Csrseri) in an official report circulated in Brussels.
"From this scientific viewpoint", we read in the footnotes, "it follows that 5-10% of those who listen to music with portable musical instruments for at least five years, more than an hour a day a week, and keep the instrument at a high volume, are at risk of permanent hearing loss".
"I am concerned that so many young people who frequently use portable musical instruments and mobile phones at high noise levels may unknowingly damage their hearing in an irreparable way", admits Meglena Kuneva.
'The scientific findings' continues the Leader's 'make clear the risk and the need to act quickly.
The most important thing is that we have to encourage consumers and make this information public.
We must continue to re-examine existing control systems in the light of this scientific finding so that they become fully effective and keep pace with new technology.'
Brussels has requested an Independent Scientific Committee to investigate this problem in view of the high use of portable musical instruments and the increasing number of young people exposed to noise of this origin.
'The scientists  concluded the EU executive  confirm that there is cause for concern and now the European Commission will examine together with the other Member States and parties that raised the problem what measures could possibly be put in place to better protect children and young people from exposure to noise caused by portable musical instruments and similar devices.'
There is already a European safety standard limiting the noise level of portable musical instruments to 100 dB, but concerns are growing about the damage to hearing that can be caused by excessive exposure to similar forms of noise.
It is very possible to limit these damages by looking for solutions such as reducing the level and duration of exposure.
In its opinion, the European Scientific Committee states that users of portable musical instruments, if they use loud music (more than 89 decibels) for only five hours a week, exceed the currently applicable limits corresponding to the maximum permissible noise level in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for a long time risk permanent hearing loss after five years.
This problem is expected to affect 5-10% of users of such devices and could be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
