Elites in Danger
This phenomenon was already evident a few days ago when the House of Representatives voted against the $700 billion bailout plan put forward by the White House: a significant proportion of Americans were more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
As confirmed by yesterday's New York Times, which informs us that the current crisis is dividing the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, more moderate, welcoming to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, which is conservative, hostile to those in Washington and the financial world, strong in the central states and the South.
The soul that arrogantly voted, the one I spoke of at the beginning...
But this is just one example of the change, the big change, that the current economic earthquake is already showing, not just in the United States, but across the West, and maybe not just here.
In both the US and Europe, this crisis seems to be acting as an accelerator for phenomena that have been in incubation for a long time, that are consolidating in the new climate and finally coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the reactivation, the extraordinary revival of the market, the dual category of the State-power in relation to a certain re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis is indeed a crisis of banking and financial institutions, which of course have strong ties abroad, but which are primarily concerned with the budgets of people and families living in one country, in one state.
Which also created a political problem for those who run it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people and families, who are also voters.
In short, the crisis appears economically global, but politically almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to be essentially out of the game or to have little to add: the clear evidence is the European Union, which is as always divided between different interests and different state strategies and which cannot decide on a single political line.
And so everyone is waiting for the intervention of the individual state government, the bailout, the market revival, the new rules and, most importantly, the distribution of funds: the moment we get into a crisis, only the states have the economic means, the amount of financial resources to be able to try and make things right.
And they also have the necessary means and the authority to use them: two resources of immense value, under certain circumstances, which perhaps no market or international organization will ever be able to dispose of to the same extent.
This new emphasis on the national-state element, which the crisis is placing, is in full accord with the increasing importance which recent economic progress is attempting to attach to a factor closely linked to it: territorial ownership.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had entered the realm of the satya, the increasingly sophisticated technology, the immaterial, while we were convinced that global finance was already destined to rule the world, out of nowhere we realized that our future would have to contend increasingly with such little immaterial things as water, grain, oil.
All the things that would be said can be transported from one place on earth to another, but they are in any case absolutely connected to a confined space, a territory.
So whoever becomes their ruler is sure to have a lot more cards on his sleeve than whoever isn't and who is unlucky enough to live in a place without grain, without oil and without water.
I'm getting to the second news, which is predicting a disaster.
When you talk about territory, state, government, you're inevitably talking about politics, which is leadership.
In view of the economic crisis, two convergent phenomena seem to be emerging.
On the one hand, the realization that there is an objective need for authoritarian leadership, the demand for someone who can handle the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discrediting of existing leadership, especially economic leadership, which has proven equally inadequate and full of dark spots.
And together, something even deeper and in a sense disturbing: the discredit, impatience, sense of incompetence and absence that is trying to control the entire ruling class in more and more Western countries.
It seems that there is a growing belief among the masses that their actions are not the same as the ideas of the elite, the way they feel and are, their culture in the true sense of the word, that the elite are out of their time and indifferent to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership is simply feeding one branch from the underground, but a strong movement to eliminate the ruling classes and the traditional political order is manifested in sudden electoral "struggles" or in unexpected changes in collective mood in recent and most recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the fall of the Labour Party in Britain to the uprising of US congressmen against Bush (and perhaps the right-wing victory in Italy has something to do with it).
We have the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their ceremonies, their newspapers, their accredited intelligence, some would say their format, are having increasing problems understanding, that is, representing, what, not today, is being created in the deepest layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis is again intensifying, spreading, potentially overwhelming.
It would be an exaggeration to speak of a permanent "mass uprising" before that.
But we can't say that means keeping our eyes wide open.
