Goodbye to the old Paradiso, the cities cancel the historic halls
The historic movie theaters are closing in favor of the Multiplex.
"A city without a cinema is like a blind man, a face without eyes".
The film, by Giuseppe Tornator, successfully documents what is happening in the major Italian urban centres as well as in the rural towns.
The process of restricting theatres, the birth of large multi-purpose halls in the suburbs and the subsequent extinction of single-purpose halls in the central areas of cities, is one of those events that seems inevitable and irreversible, but it also has all the hallmarks of a true cultural crime.
Often, historical places full of memories disappear, "it's like losing a friend, an acquaintance with whom we shared a piece of the journey and a lot of emotions", feels the director of the New Cinema Paradiso, a film that won the Tornator Oscar and the Grand Jury Prize at Cannes 20 years ago, and which tells the poetry of a village cinema and the sadness of a way of life that cinema seems to have lost forever.
The figures obtained by Anec, the main operator association, speak for themselves: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinema theatres have closed their doors, with the highest costs being borne by the most important cities: 10 fewer in Florence, 9 fewer in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 fewer in Turin, 5 fewer in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by closures, Emilia-Romagna is first with 82 cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And proof that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplexing, are the three Italian regions that have registered the highest number of new multiplex cinemas: 195 more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 more in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian process has developed irrationally", says Paolo Protti, President of Anec",it is useful to create new structures, but it would be necessary to guarantee that the existing ones survive, because when one cinema in a city closes, not all its visitors are willing to move to a multiplex.
Not to mention the insufficient subsidy to the fund in favour of operators: the previous public debt is around EUR 10 million.
From a moral and ethical standpoint, it is a shame that the government does not respect the existing laws.
The sector would need between €16 and €18 million a year to support it.
The case of Bologna is interesting, the first Italian city to be concerned about closures and to have decided to find a solution by signing a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to protect and promote small cinemas in both historic centres and suburbs.
The planned rules include tax relief measures for operators and mobility benefits for the public: spectators will be able to enter restricted traffic zones and will have special prices for stops and certain parking lots.
'I like this initiative,' says Giuseppe Tornatore, 'and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna's example by introducing other measures'.
But what is certain is that to be able to stand up to the great power of multiplexing, traditional theatres must improve the quality of sound and image, because today's audiences are more demanding.
Defending traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important: closing the Super Cinema in Bagheri, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to start the New Cinema Paradiso, which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I've lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I walk past the now-closed Rialt or Quirinal on the Nazionale, where I've shared so many emotions that I don't have to look at the black-dust signs, I turn the other way.
